RECORD 18 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE VIII. UNAUTHORIZED QUANTITIES
8.1 Unauthorized flow of gas at the Receipt Points prior to the execution of a Service Agreement will be assessed a charge of $25.00/Dth. Except in those circumstances in which the integrity of the System is threatened, Transporter shall provide Operator or Shipper with prompt notification by telephone or E- mail of such unauthorized deliveries. Operator or Shipper shall then have forty-eight (48) hours after said notification to initiate corrective action. If no action is taken by Shipper or Operator, Transporter will have the right to confiscate unauthorized gas quantities without any liability on the part of Transporter.

BBT (Midla), LLC Record 19 FERC Gas Tariff GT&C (Determination of Receipts & Deliveries) Eight Revised Volume No. 1 Version 1.0.0 ___________________________________________________________________________________
RECORD 19 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE IX. DETERMINATION OF RECEIPTS AND DELIVERIES
9.1 Receipt Point Allocation.
(a) PDA Requirement. In the event gas other than the gas transported for Shipper is measured by Transporter’s meter at each Receipt Point and Delivery Point, as set forth herein, Shipper agrees to provide, or cause to be provided to Transporter a PDA from the Operators setting forth the information described herein for the purpose of determining the quantity of gas to be received by Transporter for the account of Shipper at each Receipt Point for the Days of transportation for which Shipper has made its nominations. Transporter will support PDA methodology types: Ranked, Pro Rata, Swing Percentage, and Operator Provided Value (“OPV”). The same standard allocation methodologies should be available for use at all points. If the two parties cannot agree upon an allocation methodology, pro rata based upon confirmed nomination should be used as the default method. The party responsible for custody transfer (the party performing the measurement function) should provide the allocation.
(b) PDA Methods. The PDA provided for each Receipt Point and Delivery Point on the System shall include:
(i) An allocation by the Operator of the facilities immediately upstream of Transporter’s Receipt Point gas to be delivered at the Receipt Point on each Day of transportation service based on one of the following methods:
(A) Percentage PDA;
(B) Pro rata PDA;
(C) Ranked PDA;
(D) Swing PDA;
(E) OPV PDA; or
(F) Any other mutually agreeable allocation methodology.
(ii) A ranking by each Shipper of gas at the Receipt Point and Delivery Point for each Day of transportation service. The Operator shall rank the Service Agreements to receive its gas supplies based on one of the following methods:
(A) Pro rata PDA;
(B) Ranked PDA;
Percentage PDA;
(C) Swing PDA;
(D) OPV PDA; or
(E) Any other mutually agreeable allocation methodology.
(iii) Rankings shall include the contract number assigned by Transporter to each Service Agreement and the name of the Shipper thereunder.
(iv) The party providing an OPV PDA under Section 9.1(b) of these General Terms and Conditions will also designate the Service Agreement to be used to handle any variance between the total quantity entered for allocation at the point under the OPV PDA methodology and the total quantity measured at the point on a day. The party providing the PDA under this Section 9.1 of these General Terms and Conditions should communicate to the other shippers that their transactions for allocation purposes are lowest ranked or swing, when such shippers’ transactions are identified in the PDA submitted to Transporter by the allocating party as being lowest ranked or swing.
9.2 Pipeline Interconnects. The PDA for Receipt Points and Delivery Points interconnecting with third-party pipelines shall be provided by the third-party pipeline and shall rank the various Service Agreements to be supplied at the Receipt Point in accordance with one of the methodologies enumerated in Section 9.1(b) of these General Terms and Conditions. In the event there is a conflict between the foregoing methodologies and the third-party pipeline’s provisions in its FERC Gas Tariff governing the allocations of deliveries, said pipeline company and Transporter shall mutually agree on the PDA allocation methodology to be used. The ranking shall include the contract number assigned by Transporter to each Service Agreement and the name of the Shipper thereunder.
9.3 PDA Deadlines and Default PDA.
Each PDA for each Receipt Point and Delivery Point must be submitted to Transporter by facsimile transmission or through the Internet Website during the confirmation of that Day’s nominations or after confirmation but prior to 5:00 p.m. Central Clock Time two (2) Days following the gas Day. Transporter shall extend the PDA deadline to no later than four (4) Days following the end of the Month in which the gas was transported in the event all of the affected parties, including the Point Operator and all shippers, send notice to Transporter in writing that they are in agreement on the PDA to be used and have no objection to a change in the PDA. If no additions in nominations by a Shipper at a Receipt Point or a Delivery Point or other changes are made, the current PDA will stay in effect as submitted until it is changed pursuant to the foregoing procedures. A new allocation detail may be needed when a nomination changes. In the event Shipper tenders a nomination at a Receipt Point or at a Delivery Point from a party not currently providing or receiving gas to or from Shipper, then, as set forth above, Shipper must provide, or cause to be provided, a revised PDA at the Receipt Point or the Delivery Point which recognizes the Shipper’s nomination. In the event Transporter does not receive a PDA or revised PDA for a Receipt Point or a Delivery Point in a timely manner, each Shipper agrees that Transporter shall be authorized to allocate gas supplies at such Receipt Point or Delivery Point based on a Pro Rata PDA until Transporter receives a PDA pursuant to the above procedures which revises the Pro Rate PDA allocation on a prospective basis.
(a) Shipper hereby agrees that Transporter shall have the right to rely conclusively on the foregoing PDAs for the purposes of determine the daily quantities of gas received and delivered by (F)Transporter for the account of Shipper at each Receipt Point and Delivery Point.
9.4 Pipeline Interconnect Allocation.
(a) At any point of interconnection with another pipeline, Transporter may agree on a nondiscriminatory basis, to enter into a form of OBA with such pipeline operator in lieu of the allocation provisions of Sections 9.1 through Section 9.3 of these General Terms and Conditions, as applicable, if the following conditions are met:
(i) The pipeline Operator is creditworthy or provides one of the alternate forms of credit support set forth in Section 4 of these General Terms and Conditions;
(ii) The pipeline Operator maintains dispatching personnel on a 24-hour basis, seven days a week;
(iii) The point of interconnection is equipped with electronic measurement equipment; and
(iv) Transporter and pipeline Operator enter into an OBA which shall provide, inter alia, for the allocation of scheduled nominations at the point of interconnect with any daily variance between scheduled nominations and metered flow at such point to be resolved by Transporter and the pipeline operator under the terms of the OBA.
(b) Transporter shall maintain on its Internet Website a list of all pipeline interconnects at which an OBA is in effect.
9.5 Application of NAESB Standards’ Timelines. The NAESB timelines applicable to standard NAESB PDA methods shall also apply to any additional PDA methods offered by Transporter pursuant to the provisions of this Section 9 of these General Terms and Conditions.
9.6 Time Limit on Disputes of Allocations. In the event of an intra-day capacity recall, the Transportation Service Provider (“TSP”) should determine the allocation of capacity between the Releasing Shipper and the Replacement Shipper based upon the Elapsed Prorata Capacity (“EPC”). Variations to the use of EPC may be necessary to reflect the nature of the TSP’s tariff, services, and/or operational characteristics.

BBT (Midla), LLC Record 20 FERC Gas Tariff GT&C (Resolution of Imbalances) Eight Revised Volume No. 1 Version 1.0.0 ___________________________________________________________________________________
RECORD 20 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE X. RESOLUTION OF IMBALANCES
10.1 Obligation of Shipper to Balance. The Shipper, or Shipper’s Agent, receiving any Transportation Service from Transporter shall be responsible to use all reasonable efforts to ensure that receipts and deliveries of gas are equal to the nominations scheduled by Transporter. The Shipper shall be responsible to control and, if necessary, adjust receipts, deliveries, and confirmed nominations. To the extent that a Shipper is out of balance, it will be subject to the monthly balancing provisions contained within this Section 10 of these General Terms and Conditions.
10.2 Netting and Trading of Imbalances.
(a) If:
(i) Shipper has not been notified by Transporter that its imbalances are creating an operation problem on its System and that the continuation of the imbalance is endangering service to other Shippers,
(ii) Shipper is not able to trade its imbalance pursuant to the provisions of Transporter's imbalance netting and trading service as provided under Section 10.2(b) of these General Terms and Conditions, and
(iii) Transporter and the applicable Shipper have not mutually agreed to an alternate method, then,
(iv) Each Month Transporter and Shipper shall cash-out any imbalance between deliveries and scheduled nominations at the Delivery Points as provided under Section 10.2 of these General Terms and Conditions. Transporter shall divide the monthly imbalance by the sum of all scheduled nominations for all Days of the Month to determine the percentage monthly imbalance for the purpose of the cash-out as set forth hereinafter.
(b) Monthly Imbalance Trading and Netting Procedures.
(i) As soon as practicable following the end of each Month, but not later than the ninth (9th) Business Day, Transporter shall provide each Shipper or its Agent a statement detailing the monthly imbalance quantity that will include the netting of imbalances created under all of Shipper’s Service Agreements. Shipper or its Agent, collectively referred to as “Shipper” in this Section 10 of these General Terms and Conditions, shall have until the seventeenth (17th) Business Day of each Month to correct monthly imbalances by trading imbalances with other Shippers. Any imbalances remaining after the seventeenth (17th) Business Day shall be cashed-out pursuant to Section 10.2 of these General Terms and Conditions.
Transporter will provide the ability to post and trade imbalances at any time during the gas flow Month, and until the seventeenth Business Day after the end of the Month. Authorizations to Post Imbalances that are received by Transporter by 11:45 a.m. will be effective by 8:00 a.m. the next Business Day. Upon receipt of Authorization to Post,
Transporter shall post Shipper’s imbalances to Transporter’s Internet Website, to allow Shipper to trade the specific quantity with other Shippers. Shipper shall have the ability to view, and download such postings. Transporter shall not be required to post zero (0) imbalances.
(ii) Imbalances trades can only be withdrawn by the initiating trader and only prior to the confirming trader’s confirmation of the trade. Imbalance trades are considered final when Transporter has received an “Imbalance Trade Confirmation” confirmed by the confirming trader and effectuated by the Transporter. After receipt of an Imbalance Trade Confirmation, Transporter shall send the Imbalance Trade Notification to the initiating trader and the confirming trader no later than noon CCT the next Business Day.
(iii) After the seventeenth (17th) Business Day of the Month, Transporter shall adjust the preceding Month's imbalance to reflect the quantities traded or netted. No additional charges to the Shipper will be imposed for monthly imbalances so adjusted. All or part of a Shipper's total monthly imbalance may be offset, provided that a Shipper's total monthly imbalance that is positive may not become negative, and vice versa. Any Shipper imbalance remaining after the end of such seventeenth (17th) Business Day will be cashed out as described in Section 10.2 of these General Terms and Conditions.
10.3 Cash-Out Provision.
(a) At the end of any Month, if Shipper has a net imbalance with respect to its deliveries during the preceding Month, then Transporter shall send Shipper a statement prior to the ninth (9th) Business Day after the end of such Month that details the daily or monthly imbalance quantity and the credit due Shipper if deliveries are less than scheduled nominations in the previous Month or a bill for the amount due Transporter if deliveries are greater than scheduled nominations in the previous Month.
(b) Each Shipper’s total monthly imbalance remaining after the netting and trading period described in Section 10.2 of these General Terms and Conditions will be cashed out in accordance with the following procedures.
(c) Cash-Out. Each Month such Cash-Out Price shall be adjusted to include any transportation or other charges associated with Upstream Pipelines and by the "Cash-Out Adjustment Factor" as determined as follows:
(i) When the monthly imbalance quantity is less than zero (0), the cash-out price for the amount due Transporter shall be adjusted as follows:
Percentage Monthly Imbalance Cash-Out Adjustment Factor Up to 5,000 Dths: 100% Cash-Out Index Price If 5,000 Dths or greater: Up to 10% 100% Cash-Out Index Price
>10 - 15% 110% Cash-Out Index Price
>15 - 20% 120% Cash-Out Index Price
>20% 130% Cash-Out Index Price
(ii) When the monthly imbalance quantity is greater than zero, the cash-out price for the amount due Shipper shall be adjusted as follows:
Percentage Monthly Imbalance Cash-Out Adjustment Factor Up to 5,000 Dths:
If 5,000 Dths or greater: Up to 10% >10 - 15% 100% Cash-Out Index Price
100% Cash-Out Index Price 90% Cash-Out Index Price>15 - 20% 80% Cash-Out Index Price
>20% 70% Cash-Out Index Price
10.4 Over-Delivery Charge. In the event that the Shipper’s daily delivered quantities are greater than Shipper’s daily scheduled quantities, then a transportation charge equivalent to two times the maximum Rate Schedule ITS or ITS-N rate shall be assessed to those quantities delivered by Transporter that were in excess of the Shipper’s daily scheduled quantities.
10.5 Existing Imbalances. Imbalances existing prior to the effective date of this provision shall be corrected p ursuant to the procedures in effect at the time the imbalance was incurred.
10.6 Limitation on Penalties. Any imbalances caused by Force Majeure Condition or caused by the sole action or failure to act of Transporter, including providing the OBA parties inaccurate imbalance information at points with Electronic Data, (a) will not be included in the calculation of the total monthly imbalance for purposes of determining the appropriate cash-out level and (b) will be cashed-out at the 0-10% tolerance level in Section 10.3 of these General Terms and Conditions.
10.7 Cash-Out Revenue. By March 31 of each Year, Transporter shall compare the revenues received and the costs (including any cost under Section 10.10 of these General Terms and Conditions) incurred during the applicable annual period for Shippers’ total monthly imbalances including as a result of the cash-out procedures. Transporter (1) may use any net over-recoveries to reduce any amount owed Transporter, or add any net under-recoveries to any amount owed by Transporter, in the FL&A account, and (2) shall refund any remaining net over-recoveries or invoice for net under-recoveries pursuant to Section 28 of these General Terms and Conditions. The value in Dths of any over-recovery or under-recovery to be used in Section 28 of these General Terms and Conditions shall be the average of the Cash-Out Index Prices for the immediately preceding November.
Prior Period Adjustments. In the event a prior period adjustment to the quantities of gas booked under a Shipper’s Service Agreements occurs due to metering errors or other errors attributable to Transporter’s responsibilities under its FERC Gas Tariff, the quantity of such adjustment shall be cashed-out at the 0-
10% tolerance level in this Section 10.3 of these General Terms and Conditions for the Month in which the error occurred or the Month in which the error was discovered, whichever is to Shipper’s benefit.
10.8 Operational Integrity. Transporter shall have the right to take any action that may be required to adjust receipts and deliveries under any Service Agreement to reflect actual experience or to alleviate conditions which threaten the operational integrity of Transporter system, including without limitation maintenance of service to Shippers with a higher scheduling priority or services.
10.9 Operational Transactions. Transporter may, from time to time and in its discretion, enter into purchase or sale transactions with third parties to balance the System and to maintain operational integrity of the System. Such operational transactions may include, but not be limited to, purchases or sales:
(a) To maintain System pressure and line pack;
(b) To balance Unaccounted for Gas quantities;
(c) To resolve Shipper imbalances;
(d) To maintain an appropriate level of storage inventory; and
(e) To perform other operational functions of Transporter.
Such operational transactions shall be conducted on a not unduly discriminatory basis either by negotiating directly with individual parties or through an open season posted on Transporter’s Internet Website.

BBT (Midla), LLC Record 17 FERC Gas Tariff GT&C (Scheduling, Curtailment & Op Flow Orders) Eight Revised Volume No. 1 Version 1.0.0 ___________________________________________________________________________________
RECORD 17 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE VII. SCHEDULING, CURTAILMENT, AND OPERATIONAL FLOW ORDERS
7.1 Allocation of Available Capacity. For each nomination cycle, upon consideration of prevailing operating conditions, scheduled or unscheduled maintenance or repairs, and other conditions, Transporter shall allocate Available Capacity in the following manner from highest priority (a) to lowest priority (f) below:
(a) Anchor Shippers;
(b) Rate Schedule FTS and FTS-N Shippers receiving gas from Primary Receipt Points and delivering gas to Primary Delivery Points on a pro rata basis;
(c) Rate Schedule FTS and FTS-N Shippers receiving gas from Secondary Receipt Points or delivering gas to Secondary Delivery Points on a pro rata basis;
(d) Rate Schedule ITS and ITS-N Shippers by rate paid from highest to lowest and then, if necessary, pro rata among the Rate Schedule ITS and ITS-N Shippers who are paying the same rate; and
(e) Authorized Overruns;
(f) All other services provided by Transporter.
7.2 Scheduling Nominated Quantities. Promptly upon the close of the nomination deadline and the confirmation process for each nomination cycle, Transporter shall evaluate all confirmed nominations and the anticipated Available Capacity of the System. Transporter shall schedule nominated quantities of gas to the extent capacity is available in such a manner that all firm services will have a higher priority over interruptible services. The daily grid-wide synchronization times for scheduled flow are 9:00 a.m., 5:00 p.m., and 9:00 p.m. Central Clock Time.
7.3 Curtailment. The reverse priority set out in Section 7.1 of these General Terms and Conditions shall be utilized for interruptions and curtailments; and the rate for a service, where applicable, shall be considered from lowest to highest. For example, Shippers receiving service under Rate Schedule ITS and ITS-N (including Authorized Overrun Nominations) will be curtailed before Shippers receiving service under Rate Schedule FTS and FTS-N.
7.4 Capacity Curtailment and OFOs.
(a) Extent.
(i) If as the result of capacity constraints curtailment or interruption of service is required, then Transporter shall allocate such reduced available capacity in accordance with Section 7.1 of these General Terms and Conditions of Transporter's FERC Gas Tariff.
Where Transporter's ability to render service is impaired in a particular segment of Transporter's system, then curtailment or interruption shall be effected in accordance with the above only in that segment of Transporter's system in which service has been impaired.
(b) Operational Flow Orders: Operational Flow Order or “OFO” shall mean an order issued to alleviate conditions, inter alia, which threaten or could threaten the safe operations or integrity of Transporter’s system or to maintain operations required to provide efficient and reliable firm service. The two types of OFOs that Transporter can issue are: Balancing OFOs or Critical Day OFOs. Transporter shall have the right to issue an OFO in the event that (a) conditions exist that threaten or could threaten the safe operations or integrity of the system, or (b) corrective actions are necessary to maintain system operations at pressures required to provide efficient and reliable Firm Transportation Service. The issuance of an OFO may be the result of a major weather event, the failure of pipeline facilities, or other potential events including conditions affecting adequacy of supplies for mainline injection points, line pack, or similar situations, as well as conditions affecting Transporter’s ability to manage the system imbalances. Transporter will determine, in its reasonable judgment, the circumstances that will result in the issuance of an OFO. The issuance of an OFO will depend on the quantities of gas confirmed and scheduled, the points where the actual receipts or deliveries deviate from confirmed and scheduled quantities, whether an OBA is governing the allocation at the points, and the relationship of these individual factors to the general system operations on any given Day. Transporter shall minimize the use of OFOs and, when possible, direct an OFO to the specific parties creating the operating condition. Transporter shall lift any OFO upon cessation of conditions that warranted an OFO. To the extent that an OFO is applicable, Transporter will notify such Shippers by Electronic Notice Delivery (email). Such Electronic Notice Delivery will include a subject line that includes the following information:
(i) Time and Date of Issuance;
(ii) Time that OFO is effective; and
(iii) Type and Duration of OFO. The email message will include: (i) The meter number or class of Shipper(s) affected;
(ii) The action that Shipper(s) must take; and
(iii) The reason or justification for issuing the OFO.
If a Shipper makes a contact person available for such notices on a 24-hour basis, and provides all necessary information to Transporter, Transporter will use reasonable efforts to give actual notice to that person, as time permits.
(c) Immediate Action Critical Notice. If Transporter determines that operational circumstances exist such that the issuance of an OFO is imminent, but corrective actions may be taken to mitigate such circumstances, Transporter shall issue an Immediate Action Critical Notice to warn affected Shippers of a potential OFO. Shippers will be notified through their choice of Electronic Notice Delivery mechanism or phone. Such notice will include a subject line that includes the following information:
(i) “Critical,”
Notice Type label,
(ii) The Notice Effective Date in YYYYMMDD format,
(iii) “Transporter,” and
(iv) Transporter’s DUNS Number.
The email message will propose corrective actions to be taken by the Shipper. Transporter will postpone the issuance of an OFO declaration and allow warned Shippers the opportunity to take corrective actions, provided the warned Shippers advise Transporter of their proposed corrective actions. Failure to implement corrective measures by such Shippers may ultimately result in the issuance of an OFO by Transporter.
(d) Balancing OFO. If there is an ongoing or anticipated weather event, equipment problem or operations problem on all or part of Transporter's system, or problems exist with Transporter's line pack, that Transporter anticipates will threaten safe operations or the integrity of all or part of Transporter's system or service to any of its firm transportation customers, Transporter may declare a Balancing OFO. Unless due to circumstances beyond Transporter’s control or reasonable ability to foresee, Balancing OFOs will be issued prior to 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time to be effective at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time the following Day. In addition to the advanced notice provision in this Section 7.4, Transporter shall post on its Internet Website, with as much advance warning as is reasonably practicable, information regarding the operational variables that, or will in the future, give rise to issuance of an OFO; and Transporter will provide updates regarding the expected duration of an OFO based on those variables. Within a reasonable time period following the termination of an OFO, Transporter shall post on its Internet Website a report detailing the factors requiring the issuance and termination of an OFO. Also, OFOs affecting a number of meters on all or any portion of the system will be posted on the Internet Website. If Shipper fails to take corrective action to maintain a balance between Shipper’s actual and scheduled receipts and deliveries during a Balancing OFO, then Transporter may assess a penalty of $5.00 multiplied by each Dth of Shipper’s actual quantities at a Receipt or Delivery Points that deviate from scheduled quantities, plus or minus a safe harbor equal to the greater of (1) 2% of the daily scheduled quantities, or (2) 1,000 Dths per Day per Shipper or 500 Dths per Day per meter, when Transporter’s Balancing OFO is in effect. Transporter shall not assess a Balancing OFO penalty if Transporter’s SCADA/Real time data is unavailable to Shipper.
(e) Critical Day OFO. If the declaration of the Balancing OFO does not rectify the situation that led to the Balancing OFO or Transporter needs to address an imminent situation threatening safe operations or the integrity of all or part of Transporter's system or service to any of its firm transportation customers, Transporter may declare a Critical Day OFO. When a Critical Day OFO exists on the system and after six (6) hours prior notice to Shipper, Transporter may unilaterally make adjustments to maintain a balance between Shipper’s actual and scheduled receipts and deliveries. Transporter shall provide Shipper notice via Electronic Notice Delivery or via the Internet Website. If Shipper fails to take corrective action to maintain a balance between Shipper’s actual and scheduled receipts and deliveries during a Critical Day OFO, then Transporter may assess a penalty of $10.00 multiplied by each Dth of Shipper’s actual quantities at the Receipt or Delivery Points that deviates from scheduled quantities when Transporter’s Critical Day OFO is in effect. Transporter shall not assess a Critical Day OFO penalty if Transporter’s SCADA/Real time data is unavailable to Shipper.
Compliance with Operational Flow Orders. OFOs issued to alleviate conditions that threaten the operational integrity of the system will require compliance within the time specified in the OFO.
Any Shipper receiving an OFO may undertake any of the following actions necessary to comply with such order, as applicable:
(i) Commence or increase receipt of gas into the system by a specified quantity at a Receipt Point or shift receipt of gas, in whole or part, to a different Receipt Points;
(ii) Cease or reduce receipt of gas into the system by a specified quantity at a specified Receipt Point;
(iii) Commence or increase takes of gas from the system by a specified quantity at a specified Delivery Point; or,
(iv) Cease or reduce takes of gas from the system by a specified quantity at a specified Delivery Point.
(b) (c) (d) (e) (f) (g) If a Shipper is notified by Transporter of an OFO and fails to comply with such OFO, such Shipper may be subject to the applicable OFO penalty set forth in Sections 7.4(c) and (d) multiplied by each Dth received or delivered in excess of the quantities specified by Transporter in such OFO (except to the extent of the safe harbor with respect to Balancing OFOs). If such Shipper complies by adjusting its receipts or deliveries within the time period specified in an OFO, the Shipper shall not be subject to the OFO penalty set forth in Section 7.4(c) and (d). Shipper compliance shall be a change in gas flow to the level specified by Transporter and will be evidenced by the confirmation of a flow rate change from an upstream or downstream point operator or the confirmation of a flow rate change by Transporter. Transporter will assist any Shipper in complying with an OFO. Transporter will not impose a penalty for failure to comply if that Shipper demonstrates that it has taken all reasonable efforts to comply, including taking other actions (in consultation with Transporter) to achieve the purpose of the OFO, and Shipper sought Transporter’s assistance within the time specified in the OFO for commencement of corrective action. Transporter will not impose an OFO penalty if penalties are incurred due to Shipper’s compliance with the OFO, including preliminary action taken in response to an Immediate Action Critical Notice issued by Transporter. Unless critical circumstances dictate otherwise, where a nomination is required by Transporter to make an effective physical change necessary to comply with an OFO, an OFO penalty will not be assessed unless the Shipper has the opportunity to correct the circumstances giving rise to the OFO and either fails to do so or the actions taken by the Shipper fail to do so. The opportunity to correct the critical circumstances will include the opportunity (a) to make a nomination that, once confirmed and scheduled, would cure the circumstance giving rise to the OFO; or (b) to take other appropriate action that cures the circumstance giving rise to the OFO. A Shipper’s response to an OFO will not be constrained by restrictions on the submittal, confirmation and processing of Intra-Day Nominations.
(h) Operational Flow Orders by Upstream or Downstream Point Operators or Pipelines. To the extent an upstream or downstream point operator or pipeline issues an OFO or similar order, Transporter will notify Shippers of such order as soon as practicable and direct Shippers to respond accordingly and within the time limits specified by the upstream or downstream pipeline. If a Shipper fails to respond to such order, Transporter will assess such Shippers the respective penalties or charges incurred and paid by Transporter to the upstream or downstream point operator or pipeline.
Imbalances Resulting from Operational Flow Orders.
(i) To the extent any monthly imbalance or portion thereof is a direct result of Shipper’s inability to balance receipts and deliveries during the Month due to the issuance of an OFO, Shipper will have until the end of the next Month to reconcile that portion of the imbalance attributable to its compliance with the OFO. Shipper shall submit a plan to Transporter to reconcile such imbalances to Transporter.
(ii) To the extent a plan accepted by Transporter cannot be executed because of actions taken by Transporter, Shipper will have an additional Month to correct an OFO-based imbalance. Any imbalance remaining at the end of the extended period will be subject to the imbalance resolution procedures set forth in Section 3.7 of the General Terms and Conditions of Transporter’s FERC Gas Tariff.
7.2 7.3 7.4 7.5 Excess Hourly Takes. If a Critical Day OFO applicable to Shipper is in effect and Shipper exceeds its permitted hourly allowance of quantities to Transporter at a Receipt Point or from Transporter at a Delivery Point, then Transporter shall assess a penalty of $25.00 for each Dth in excess of Shipper’s hourly allowance.
7.6 Penalty Crediting Mechanism.
(a) Shipper shall pay only one penalty or charge for each Day when Shipper’s actions result in either Balancing OFO penalties, Critical Day OFO penalties, penalties for excess hourly or daily quantities, or penalties or charges assessed by upstream or downstream pipeline. Shipper will pay the higher of these penalties or charges and at no time will Shipper be assessed multiple or additive penalties for Shipper’s actions during each Day an OFO is in effect.
(b) To the extent that OFO penalties and penalties for excess hourly quantities are received by Transporter that are in excess of Transporter’s costs including but not limited to Transporter’s costs to purchase or sell gas to alleviate any adverse operational conditions, Transporter will refund all excess OFO penalty revenue to Shippers in a non OFO penalty position using the methodology used by Transporter with respect to cash-out revenues as set forth in Section 27 of these General Terms and Conditions of Transporter’s FERC Gas Tariff.

RECORD 15 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE V. REQUESTS FOR SERVICE
5.1 Request for Service. Each Shipper requesting Service under one of the Rate Schedules in this FERC Gas Tariff shall provide the following information:
(a) Shipper Identity. The identity of the Shipper making the Request for Service, including the legal name of the Shipper, the type of entity (i.e. corporation, limited partnership, etc.), a W-9 Form from Shipper, and the Shipper's DUNS Number or Federal Tax ID shall be provided.
(b) Contact and Billing. Shipper shall provide address, phone, e-mail, and other contact information for ongoing business, notices, and billings required by Transporter to complete the appropriate Service Agreement.
(c) Credit Information. Shipper shall provide credit information as required by Transporter in accordance with Section 4 of these General Terms and Conditions. Service is contingent upon a satisfactory credit appraisal and maintenance of a satisfactory credit record pursuant to Section 4 of these General Terms and Conditions. Transporter may require information, deny service, or require security as set forth in Section 4 of these General Terms and Conditions.
(d) Request Type. Shipper must indicate if the Request for Service is for new service or to amend an existing contract. Amendment requests require the existing Contract Number which is to be amended.
(e) Rate Schedule. Shipper shall indicate the applicable Rate Schedule for such Service.
(f) Rate. Shipper shall provide its requested rate for evaluation. The maximum rate will otherwise apply.
(g) Term of Service.
(i) Shipper shall provide the date service is requested to commence.
(ii) Shipper shall provide the requested duration of service in accordance with the applicable rate schedule.
(h) Shipper Statements. Shipper shall include statements which provide that:
(i) Shipper has title to the gas delivered to Transporter for transportation.
(ii) Shipper has entered into or will enter into those arrangements necessary to assure all upstream and downstream transportation will be in place prior to the commencement of transportation through Transporter' system.
Shipper Type. Shipper shall indicate whether it is a local distribution company, an interstate pipeline, an intrastate pipeline, an end-user, a producer, or a marketer.
(i) Agency Agreement. If the transportation agreement is to be signed with a party acting as agent for a principal, then a copy of the Agency Agreement must be provided.
(j) Other Information. Shipper shall provide such other information as is required to comply with regulatory requirements.
5.2 Information for All Firm Transportation Service.
(a) Gas Quantities. Shipper shall provide the Firm MDQ stated in Dths, which will represent Transporter' maximum daily quantities to be provided under the applicable Rate Schedule. Shipper shall indicate if Shipper is willing to accept a lesser quantity based upon capacity availability or auction results.
(b) Maximum Quantity Obligation. As specified below, for each Primary Receipt Point and Primary Delivery Point, the maximum quantity obligation for each point shall be stated individually in Dths. The sum of the maximum quantities stated for all Primary Delivery Points cannot exceed the total Firm MDQ.
(c) Primary Receipt Points. Shipper shall provide the Receipt Points into Transporter’s system where Shipper desires capacity to be reserved on a firm basis.
(d) Primary Delivery Points. Shipper shall provide the Delivery Points from Transporter’s System where Shipper desires capacity to be reserved on a firm basis.
(e) Affiliation. Any affiliation between Transporter and the potential Shipper or between a releasing and replacement shipper must be provided.
5.3 Information for All Interruptible Services.
(a) Receipt Points. Receipt Points are the points of entry into the System. The Transporter master receipt point listing is available on the Transporter’s Internet Website.
(b) Delivery Points. Delivery Points are the points where gas is to be delivered by Transporter. The Transporter master delivery point listing is available on the Transporter Internet Website.
(c) Gas Quantities. Shipper shall provide the MDQ, stated in Dths, which it desires to be provided under the applicable Rate Schedule.
5.4 Incomplete Service Forms. Request for Service received by Transporter that do not contain all the information specified in this Section 5 of these General Terms and Conditions, including credit information sufficient to demonstrate that a Shipper will be able to meet its financial obligations under the requested rate schedule, will be considered incomplete. Transporter will notify Shipper in writing of any deficiencies of a request; and Shipper shall provide the additional information required for a valid request within thirty (30) days. Incomplete requests for service that are not completed within thirty (30) days of a deficiency notification shall be deemed a nullity for all present and future purposes.
5.5 Forms. Requests for Service may be made utilizing the form provided for in on Transporter’s Internet Website. __________________________________________________________________________________ Issued: February 10, 2020

RECORD 21 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE XI. BILLING AND PAYMENT
11.1 Billing.
(a) Transporter will render its bill on or before the ninth (9th) Business Day of each Month for the charges due for services rendered under a Service Agreement during the previous Month, computed in accordance with the Shipper’s applicable rate schedule. Invoices will be mathematically accurate and calculated using the net billing rate. Unless otherwise agreed, invoices will state the net billing rate rather than the applicable maximum tariff rate and discount amount. Invoices will be based on actuals (if available) or best available data. Quantities at points where OBAs exist will be invoiced based on scheduled quantities.
(b) Transporter will render a written invoice or an electronic invoice to Shipper, unless Shipper requests that Transporter render an invoice via EDI. Both written and electronic invoices will use the description, charge codes, and common codes set forth in the NAESB Standards. Invoices will specify all rate components. Transporter will provide supporting data, if applicable, at the time it renders invoices. To the extent additional supporting information is requested, such information will be provided within five (5) Business Days of a request.
(c) Upon request, Transporter will provide Shipper a statement of account on which it will report outstanding balances by invoices.
11.2 Payments to Transporter.
(a) Shipper agrees to make payment to Transporter for services or any other charges within ten (10) Days from the date the invoice is rendered. Such payment shall include supporting documentation and remittance detail, including identification of invoice numbers being paid. Unless another suitable method of payment is agreed to by Transporter, Shipper shall make payment via Federal Reserve wire transfer to the bank and account designated by Transporter. Remittance detail supporting the wire transfer must be mailed, faxed, or sent via EDI within twenty-four (24) hours of the wire transfer payment to the address designated in a Service Agreement. Transporter will apply payments in accordance with the supporting documentation and remittance detail provided by the Shipper; and if payment differs from invoiced amount, remittance detail will be provided with the payment unless payment is made by electronic funds transfer, in which case, the remittance detail is due within two (2) Business Days of the payment due date. Should Shipper fail to pay all of the amount of any bill for service or any additional charges hereunder when such amount is due, interest on the unpaid portion shall accrue at an interest rate equal to the current FERC interest rate, as defined in Section 154.501(d) of FERC’s regulations, from the date due until the date payment is received by Transporter.
In the event Shipper, in good faith, shall dispute the amount of any such bill, Shipper shall pay the portion not in dispute within ten (10) Days from the date the invoice is rendered and provide documentation of the basis for the dispute. If by agreement, arbitration, dispute resolution, other forms of mediation, or judgment of the courts, a portion of Shipper’s bill that has been paid is reduced, Transporter shall pay interest on the overpaid portion of said bill, such interest accruing from the date payment is received by Transporter until the time refunds are made to
Shipper at an interest rate equal to the current FERC interest rate as defined above. Unless otherwise specified in a Service Agreement, the effective payment date of an invoice when such due date does not fall upon a Business Day will be the first Business Day following the due date.
(b) If such failure to pay for services or any additional charges continues for thirty (30) Days after such payment is due, in addition to any other remedy, Transporter may without liability, suspend further delivery of gas until any overdue amount is paid. However, if Shipper, in good faith, shall dispute the amount of any such bill or part thereof, Shipper shall pay Transporter in a timely manner such amounts as it concedes to be correct and, at any time thereafter within ten (10) Days of a demand made by Transporter, shall (a) furnish a good and sufficient surety bond, in amount and with sureties satisfactory to Transporter, or (b) place such disputed amounts in escrow, both conditioned upon the payment of any amounts ultimately found due upon such bills after final determination, which may be reached either by agreement , arbitration, dispute resolution, other forms of mediation, or judgment of the courts. Transporter shall not be entitled to suspend further delivery of gas unless and until default be made in the conditions of such bond or escrow account.
11.3 Adjustment of Billing Errors.
(a) In the event an error is discovered in the amount billed or in any statement rendered by Transporter, such error shall be adjusted within thirty (30) days of the determination thereof; provided, however, that any claim for adjustment must be made within six (6) Months from the date of such statement. Shipper will have no less than three (3) Months to dispute an adjustment. Adjustments may be made after this time period if all affected parties agree. This time limit will not apply in the case of deliberate omission or misrepresentation or mutual mistake of fact. Parties’ other statutory or contractual rights will not otherwise be diminished by this provision. In the event that any portion of a statement is in dispute, payment of the disputed portion shall not be deemed a waiver of the right to contest such disputed portion in any forum having jurisdiction in the premises. Mutual agreement between parties, legal decisions, and regulatory guidance may be necessary to determine if the event qualifies for an extension of the above time periods.
(b) Prior period adjustments will be reported by delivery Month.
11.4 Fees. Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for all fees required by FERC, or any regulatory body, which are attributable to service provided under a Service Agreement including filing, reporting, and application fees

RECORD 26 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE XVI. MEASURING EQUIPMENT
16.1 Meters.
(a) If orifice meters are used in the measurement of gas to be delivered to the Transporter, such meters shall be designed, installed and operated in accordance with specifications of the American Gas Association (AGA) Report No. 3, Part 2, Specification and Installation Requirements, and AGA Report No. 3, Part 3, Natural Gas Applications, latest revision.
(b) If ultrasonic meters are used in the measurement of gas to be delivered to the Transporter, such meters shall be designed, installed and operated in accordance with specifications of the American Gas Association (AGA) Report No. 9, Measurement of Gas by Multipath Ultrasonic Meters, latest revision
(c) If turbine meters are used in the measurement of gas to be delivered to the Transporter, such meters shall be designed, installed and operated in accordance with specifications of the American Gas Association (AGA) Report No. 7, Measurement of Gas by Turbine Meters, latest revision
(d) If rotary positive displacement meters are used in the measurement of gas to be delivered to the Transporter, such meters shall be designed, installed, and operated in accordance with specifications of the American Gas Association (AGA) Report No. 9, Measurement of Gas by Multipath Ultrasonic Meters, latest revision.
16.2 Electronic Flow Measurement. The Electronic Flow Measurement (EFM) system shall be capable of establishing an audit trail by compiling and retaining sufficient electronic data and information for the purpose of verifying daily and hourly quantities, and shall comply with the American Petroleum Institute, Manual of Petroleum Measurement Standards, Chapter 21, Section 1 - Electronic Gas Measurement (API Chapter 21.1). The Transporter shall preserve audit trail information for a minimum of 5 years or the time required by any governmental agency, whichever is greater.
16.3 Check Measurement. Shipper may, at its option and expense, install check meter equipment upstream of Transporter’s measurement station for checking the Transporter’s metering equipment. Such measurement equipment shall be installed so as not to interfere with the operation of Transporter’s facilities and shall comply with the standards set forth in this Statement. In addition, Shipper may install, at the transporters discretion, a check EFM device on Transporter’s meter run utilizing a separate set of taps on the same orifice fitting. This system shall be installed so as not to interfere with the operation of Transporter’s facility.
16.4 Pulsation. When gas compressors are located close to and either upstream or downstream of the meter station, a pulsation dampener shall be installed in the piping between the compressor and the meter station. If pulsation induced measurement errors are found to be +0.2% it will be the responsibility of the Shipper to reduce the error to that level or a higher level acceptable to Transporter.
Gas Sampling.
(a) Shipper will determine the specific gravity, the Gross Heating Value, and composition of the gas by taking a representative sample according to the schedule below. Sampling or collection shall be performed during Shipper’s scheduled meter inspection and calibration test and all samples shall be obtained and analyzed using Gas Processors Association (GPA) Standard, 2261, Analysis for Natural Gas and Similar Gaseous Mixtures by Gas Chromatograph. These analytical results shall be applied at the beginning of the Month the sample was taken and until a subsequent representative sample is applied.
(b) The sampling rate shall be determined on the following volumetric basis:
(i) For daily average flow rates of 500 MCF/D or less, on a monthly basis, the sample rate shall be semi-annual (every (6) months).
(ii) For daily average flow rates greater than 500 MCF/D and less than 5000 MCF/D, on a monthly basis, the sampling rate shall be quarterly.
(iii) For average daily flow rates greater than 5000 MCF/D, on a monthly basis, the sampling rate shall be monthly.
(c) Samples collected by spot or continuous, proportional to flow, sampling methods shall be collected using procedures and equipment specified in Gas Processors Association (GPA) Standard, 2166, Obtaining Natural Gas Samples for Analysis by Gas Chromatography or in the American Petroleum Institute (API) Manual of Petroleum Measurement Standards (MPMS), Chapter 14, Section 1, Collecting and Handling of Natural Gas Samples for Custody Transfer, latest revisions.
(d) When a gas chromatograph is used to determine the real-time Hexanes plus quantity, the applicable physical properties required for the characterization of the Hexanes plus quantity shall be determined using an extended analysis as detailed in Gas Processors Association (GPA) Standard, 2261, Analysis for Natural Gas and Similar Gaseous Mixtures by Gas Chromatograph, or upon an allocation of representative components and associated physical properties as per Gas Processors Association (GPA) Standard, 2145, Table of Physical Constants for Hydrocarbons and Other Compounds of Interest to the Natural gas Industry, latest revision. The on-line gas chromatograph used for the analysis of natural gas shall be standardized daily.
(e) Shipper shall have the right to obtain a duplicate sample of Shipper’s gas. If a difference between Transporter and Shipper’s duplicate sample exceeds one-half percent (0.5%) in MMBtu, then Shipper shall have the right to call for retest and the analysis from the preceding period shall be used until the results can be verified or a representative sample is obtained and applied. Upon written request to Gas Measurement Services, the Shipper shall furnish the requesting Party with their natural gas sample, chromatographic gas analysis report, or any other information, which may be required to verify the other Party’s analytical procedures or results.
16.2 16.3 16.4 16.5 16.6 Calibration.
Shipper shall have the right to have a representative present at the time of any installing, cleaning, changing, repairing, inspecting, testing, calibrating, or adjusting done in connection with the equipment used in measuring gas deliveries hereunder.
(a) Shipper shall also inspect, prove, and calibrate or cause to be calibrated the meters and instruments used for measurement hereunder. Transporter shall give Shipper sufficient advance notice so Shipper may, at its election, have a representative present at such tests. In the event either Party shall notify the other Party that it desires a special test of any measurement equipment, the Parties shall cooperate to secure a prompt verification of the accuracy of such equipment. The expense of any such special test, if requested, shall be borne by the Party requesting the test if the measuring equipment tested is found not to be in error or to be in composite error by not more than one percent (1%).
16.7 Corrections.
(a) If, upon test, the aggregate error of all measuring equipment, excluding gas chromatographs, is not in excess of two percent (2%), previous recordings of such equipment shall be considered accurate for computing deliveries to the Transporter. A calibration shall be performed on any measuring equipment found in error by an amount in excess of that specified in API Chapter 21.1 or any other level agreed to by both Parties.
(b) If, upon test, any measuring equipment shall be found, in aggregate, to be inaccurate by an amount exceeding two percent (2%) of all measurement parameters and associated measuring equipment under review, at a recording corresponding to the average hourly rate of flow for the period since the last test, or a material volume at the discretion of the Transporter, such equipment shall be corrected to zero error for any period which is known definitely, but in case the period is not known or agreed upon, such correction shall be for a period equal to one-half of the time elapsed since the date of the last test, but in no event for a period exceeding 30 days.
(c) Where unacceptable measurement differences exist and all other tests have been conducted to remedy the error, the orifice meter run shall be inspected and tests shall be performed to verify compliance with current AGA Committee No. 3, Part 2, Specification and Installation Requirements, as amended from time to time.
(d) If for any reason the meter is out of service or repair so that the quantity of gas deliveries through such meter cannot be ascertained or computed from the readings thereof, the quantity of gas so delivered during the period when the meter is out of service or repair shall be determined on the basis of the first of the following methods which is feasible, as agreed between the parties.
(i) By using the registration of any check measuring equipment, if such equipment is recording accurately. The Transporter shall witness and audit such measurement in the same manner that it would any custody transfer measurement equipment;
(ii) Or, in the absence of (i), by using the cumulative volumes from any field measurement source adjusting for historical differences and/or fuel consumption between the field meters and sales.
(iii) Or, in the absence of (i) or (ii), y correcting the error, if possible, by calibration, tests, or mathematical calculation.
Or, in the absence of (i), (ii), or (iii), by estimating the quantity received or delivered by receipts or deliveries during periods under similar conditions when the meter was verified to be registering correctly.
16.8 Prior Period Adjustment.
(a) All adjustments will be taken back to the delivery Month. A meter adjustment becomes a prior period adjustment after the final measurement close of the Month. All missing or late measurement data will be estimated and actual data will be treated as a prior period adjustment. The measuring party is responsible for providing the estimated volume to be used.
16.9 Errors. In the event a meter is out of service or registering inaccurately, the quantities of Gas received or delivered during such period shall be determined as follows:
(a) By using the registration of any check meter or meters, if installed and accurately registering; or
(b) In the absence of subsection (a), by correcting the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, tests or mathematical calculation; or
(c) In the absence of both subsection (a) and (b), by estimating the quantity received or delivered by receipts or deliveries during preceding periods under similar conditions when the meter was registering accurately.
16.10 Requesting Charts and Records. Each party shall, upon request of the other, mail or deliver for checking and calculation all volume and temperature meter charts in its possession and used in the measurement of Gas received or delivered hereunder within thirty (30) Days after the last chart for each billing period is removed from the meter. Such charts shall be returned within thirty (30) Days after the receipt thereof. Where electric measurement is used for custody transfer of the Gas, the standard audit package will be supplied by the measuring party.
16.11 Preservation of Records. Each party shall preserve or cause to be preserved for mutual use all test data, charts or other similar records in accordance with the applicable rules and regulations of any regulatory bodies having jurisdiction with respect to the retention of such records, and, in any event, for at least two (2) Years.

As more particularly described in Section 12 of these General Terms and Conditions, Transporter shall administer each Shipper’s release of firm capacity exclusively through its Internet Website and shall provide to Shipper other interactive capabilities such as the ability to request service, amendments, or discounts; submit nominations, confirmations, and PDAs; view information on Agents that administer or perform appointed functions for Shipper under its Service Agreements; and execute Service Agreements and amendments thereto. Service Agreement specific notices requiring communications to be in writing remain unchanged unless agreed to otherwise by the parties. Submission of information, communications, and execution of documents through Transporter’s Internet Website shall be legally binding on Shipper. Transporter may also require written execution of Service Agreements by Shipper for its records.
18.3 Content of Internet Website. Transporter’s Internet Website will display current information first, have on- line help, a menu of available information for ease of reference, and search functions. Any party will be able to download information provided on Transporter’s Internet Webpage. Transporter shall maintain and retain daily back-up records of the information displayed on its Internet Website for a period of three (3) years for purposes of restoring such information to on-line availability if a computer malfunction or loss occurs. Completed transactions and posted information will remain on Transporter’s Internet Website for at least thirty (30) Days and then will be archived. Archived information will be available from Transporter upon fifteen (15) days’ prior written notice. Copies of archived information will be made available at $0.25 per page if a paper copy is requested, $25.00 per diskette, or $35.00 per stick drive. Transporter may require parties to execute an Internet access agreement located on its Internet Website in order to gain access to the customer specific portion of its Internet Website.

RECORD 25 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE XV. RECEIPT POINT, DELIVERY POINT, AND MEASUREMENT
15.1 Base Conditions.
(a) The unit of volume for measurement of gas delivered shall be one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of gas at a base temperature of sixty (60° F) degrees Fahrenheit and at an absolute pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch, absolute (14.73 psia). All volumes shall be measured and calculated according to the current standards prescribed in the currently applicable American Gas Association publications pertaining to the primary measurement device as amended from time to time or as mutually agreed upon between the Parties.
(b) For purposes of measurement hereunder, the atmospheric pressure shall be assumed to be fourteen and seventy hundredths per square inch (14.70 psia) irrespective of variations in the actual atmospheric pressure from time to time.
15.2 Recalculation. Any volume recalculation shall utilize a mutually agreeable technique to compensate for the inherent inaccuracy associated with calculating volumes from averages of the flowing parameters as opposed to the actual instantaneous values used by the original flow-computing device.
15.3 Quality Basis.
(a) The total energy value of gas delivered shall be reported in dekatherms, as the product of volumes measured and the Gross Heating Value determined.
(b) Heating values shall be expressed in BTU’s per cubic foot, determined by calculation from compositional analysis according to the Gas Processors Association (GPA) Publication 2172, Calculation of Gross Heating Value, Specific Gravity, and Compressibility of Natural Gas Mixtures from Compositional Analysis (latest revision). Heating values shall be converted to Gross Heating Values that reflect adjustments from actual delivery conditions for temperature, pressure, water content, and compressibility.
(c) Gas produced and not dehydrated at the point of measurement shall be considered saturated with water at measurement temperature and pressure unless determined otherwise. Gas dehydrated to a water content not exceeding seven (7) pounds per thousand standard cubic feet shall be considered dry.
Receipt Point. The Receipt Point shall be at the inlet side of Transporter's measuring facilities at the point of connection between the facilities of Transporter and those of Shipper as set forth in the applicable Transportation Agreement. Should any of Transporter's lines, meters, and like equipment which is necessary for Transporter to install at or near the Receipt Point be on property of Shipper, Shipper grants to Transporter the right of free use of such premises and ingress and egress to such facilities at all times for the purpose of installation, operation, repair, or removal. Such facilities of Transporter shall be and remain the property of Transporter and may be removed upon the termination of deliveries to Shipper.
15.4 Delivery Point. The Delivery Point shall be at the outlet side of Transporter's measuring facilities at the point of connection between the facilities of Transporter and those of Shipper as set forth in the applicable Transportation Agreement. Should any of Transporter's lines, meters, and like equipment which is necessary for Transporter to install at or near the Delivery Point of delivery be on property of Shipper, Shipper grants to Transporter the right of free use of such premises and ingress and egress to such facilities at all times for the purpose of installation, operation, repair, or removal. Such facilities of Transporter shall be and remain the property of Transporter and may be removed upon the termination of deliveries to Shipper.

RECORD 22 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE XII. CAPACITY RELEASE
12.1 Eligibility. Any Shipper with an FTS or FTS-N Agreement is eligible to release all or part of its capacity to a Replacement Shipper on a permanent or temporary basis, subject to the provisions of this Section 12 of these General Terms and Conditions.
12.2 Types and Conditions of Releases.
(a) Permanent Release. A Releasing Shipper may release all or part of its firm capacity under an FTS or FTS-N Agreement for the entire remaining Primary Term of the FTS or FTS-N Agreement (“Permanent Release”). The Replacement Shipper must contract for the Primary Receipt Points and the Primary Delivery Points specifically set forth in a Releasing Shipper’s FTS or FTS-N Agreement. A Permanent Release operates as an assignment of capacity and, except as provided below with respect to continuing payment obligations, all of the terms and conditions applicable to Firm Transportation Service including the requirements related to creditworthiness must be met by the Replacement Shipper prior to the effective date of the assignment. The Replacement Shipper shall execute a separate FTS or FTS-N Agreement for the released capacity at the rate bid by the Replacement Shipper and accepted by the Releasing Shipper up to the applicable maximum tariff rate (except as provided for herein) and for the Primary Term originally set forth in the Releasing Shipper’s FTS or FTS-N Agreement with Transporter. The Releasing Shipper will remain obligated to pay the difference, if any, between the accepted bid and the applicable rate for the remainder of the existing FTS or FTS-N Agreement term. Permanent Releases with a remaining term of one (1) year or less, if the release is to take effect on or before one (1) year from the date on which Transporter is notified of the release, may be in excess of the maximum tariff rate. The rate for all other Permanent Releases with a remaining term of one year or less, and for a Permanent Release with a term greater than one (1) year may not exceed the applicable maximum tariff rate. Notwithstanding anything herein to the contrary, Transporter may refuse to allow a Permanent Release if it has a reasonable basis to conclude that it will not be financially indifferent to the release. A Replacement Shipper may not permanently release the capacity it was awarded from a Temporary Release.
(b) Temporary Release. A Releasing Shipper may temporarily release all or part of its firm capacity for a specified term without a right of recall (“Temporary Release”). The minimum term for any Temporary Release is one (1) Day. A Replacement Shipper who is awarded firm capacity pursuant to a Temporary Release shall execute a form of an FTS or FTS-N Agreement, which will be for the released capacity at the rate bid by the Replacement Shipper and accepted by the Releasing Shipper, up to the applicable maximum tariff rate (except as provided for herein) and for the term bid by the Replacement Shipper. For Temporary Releases with terms of one (1) year or less, if the release is to take effect on or before one (1) year from the date on which Transporter is notified of the release, bids may be at a rate in excess of the applicable maximum tariff rate. All other Temporary Releases with terms of one (1) year or less, and Temporary Releases with terms greater than one (1) year are capped at the applicable maximum tariff rate.
Temporary Release - Subject to Recall. A Releasing Shipper may temporarily release all or part of its firm capacity subject to recall by the Releasing Shipper upon the occurrence of the conditions specified in the Releasing Shipper’s offer to release firm capacity. The minimum term for any
Temporary Release subject to recall will be one (1) Day. A Replacement Shipper who is awarded capacity pursuant to a Temporary Release subject to recall shall execute an FTS or FTS-N Agreement which will be for the released capacity, subject to the right of recall, at the rate bid by the Replacement Shipper, and for the term bid by the Replacement Shipper.
(c) Recall Rights.
(i) A Releasing Shipper must define at the time of the release the conditions under which the released firm capacity will be recalled. Such recall conditions shall not be inconsistent with the terms and conditions of the Releasing Shipper’s FTS or FTS-N Agreement or with the provisions of this FERC Gas Tariff. The recall conditions specified by the Releasing Shipper must involve identifiable events. A Releasing Shipper may, to the extent permitted as a condition of the capacity release, recall released capacity by providing notice to Transporter and affected Replacement Shippers (by a mode mutually agreeable to the parties) on or before the Day that nominations are due by the following times for each cycle: For the recall notification provided to Transporter, including intra-day capacity recall, the quantity shall be expressed in terms of adjusted total released capacity entitlements based upon the Elapsed Pro Rata Capacity.
(A) Timely Recall Notification (all times are in Central Clock Time):
(I) A Releasing Shipper recalling capacity should provide notice of such recall to the TSP and the first Replacement Shipper no later than 8:00 a.m. on the Day that Timely Nominations are due; and
(II) The TSP should provide notification of such recall to all affected Replacement Shippers no later than 9:00 a.m. on the Day that Timely Nominations are due.
(B) Early Evening Recall Notification (all times are in Central Clock Time):
(I) A Releasing Shipper recalling capacity should provide notice of such recall to the TSP and the first Replacement Shipper no later than 3:00 p.m. on the Day that Evening Nominations are due; and
(II) The TSP should provide notification of such recall to all affected Replacement Shippers no later than 4:00 p.m. on the Day that Evening Nominations are due.
(C) Evening Recall Notification (all times are in Central Clock Time):
(I) A Releasing Shipper recalling capacity should provide notice of such recall to the TSP and the first Replacement Shipper no later than 5:00 p.m. on the Day that Evening Nominations are due; and
(II) The TSP should provide notification of such recall to all affected Replacement Shippers no later than 6:00 p.m. on the Day that Evening Nominations are due.
Intraday 1 Recall Notification (all times are in Central Clock Time):
(I) A Releasing Shipper recalling capacity should provide notice of such recall to the TSP and the first Replacement Shipper no later than 7:00 a.m. on the Day that Intraday 1 Nominations are due; and
(II) The TSP should provide notification of such recall to all affected Replacement Shippers no later than 8:00 a.m. on the Day that Intraday 1 Nominations are due.
(B) (C) (D) (E) Intraday 2 Recall Notification (all times are in Central Clock Time):
(I) A Releasing Shipper recalling capacity should provide notice of such recall to the TSP and the first Replacement Shipper no later than 12:00 Noon on the Day that Intraday 2 Nominations are due; and
(II) The TSP should provide notification of such recall to all affected Replacement Shippers no later than 3:30 p.m. on the Day that Intraday 2 Nominations are due.
(F) Intraday 3 Recall Notification (all times are in Central Clock Time):
(I) A Releasing Shipper recalling capacity should provide notice of such recall to the TSP and the first replacement Shipper no later than 4:00 p.m. on the Day that Intraday 3 Nominations are due; and
(II) The TSP should provide notification of such recall to all affected Replacement Shippers no than 5:00 p.m. on the day that Intraday 3 Nominations are due.
(G) Notification to Replacement Shippers will be provided by Transporter within one hour of receipt of recall notification. Service flexibility available to either the Releasing Shipper or the Replacement Shippers for the subject capacity shall not be less as a result of the recall. The Replacement Shipper shall be obligated to pay Transporter the Usage Rate mutually agreed to between the Releasing Shipper and Replacement Shipper, all associated volumetric surcharges applicable to the quantities Transporter transports under the Replacement Shipper’s FTS or FTS-N Agreement, and any penalties assessed in connection with the Replacement Shipper’s use of the released capacity. Transporter will retain the minimum Usage Rate, associated volumetric surcharges, and any penalty revenues. Unless Transporter has otherwise agreed in writing, Transporter shall not be required to credit all Reservation Rate revenues billed to the Replacement Shipper to the extent a Releasing Shipper’s FTS or FTS-N Agreement under which it pays a discount provides otherwise with respect to credits in excess of the Releasing Shipper’s discount.
12.10 Prequalification of Creditworthiness.
(a) All parties desiring to bid on firm capacity offered by a Releasing Shipper and all Prearranged Replacement Shippers must meet Transporter’s creditworthiness requirements and be prequalified before bidding on any Offer to Release Firm Capacity. All parties desiring to bid on firm capacity offered by a Releasing Shipper shall submit sufficient credit information to Transporter at least five (5) Business Days prior to the date on which bids for the firm capacity are to be received, so that Transporter can determine the bidder’s creditworthiness, unless Transporter agrees it has already determined the bidder to be creditworthy or to have suitable credit on file with Transporter. A bidder’s creditworthiness shall be assessed in accordance with the terms of Section 4 of these General Terms and Conditions.
(b) A party that does not qualify as a creditworthy bidder is ineligible to bid on capacity. After Transporter has determined a bidder creditworthy and eligible to bid, Transporter will issue a Bidder Prequalification Number to the bidder. Once a bidder is issued a Bidder Prequalification Number, it is not necessary for that bidder to resubmit credit information for prequalification, except as requested by Transporter from time to time.
(c) In the case of releases not subject to bidding, the Prearranged Replacement Shipper must prequalify at least five (5) Business Days prior to Transporter’s nomination deadline for transportation using the released capacity. In all other respects, the terms and conditions applicable to bidders also apply to the Prearranged Replacement Shippers who have not otherwise complied with the above requirements.
12.11 Responsibilities of Releasing Shippers. The Releasing Shipper shall remain fully liable under its existing Gas Transportation Agreement with Transporter for the payment of all reservation charges each Month for the full contract quantity, whether or not such quantity has been released. As permitted by this Section 12, a Shipper may release all or part of its firm capacity on a permanent or temporary basis. The Releasing Shipper will remain obligated to pay the difference, if any, between the accepted bid and the applicable rate for the remainder of the existing Gas Transportation Agreement term. A Releasing Shipper shall be responsible for notifying, or causing to be notified, its Replacement Shipper prior to exercising recall rights, as specified in Section 12.2 of these General Terms and Conditions.
Responsibilities of Replacement Shippers. A Replacement Shipper awarded capacity under a Permanent Release shall execute a separate FTS or FTS-N Agreement with Transporter for the released capacity at the rate bid by the Replacement Shipper and accepted by the Releasing Shipper up to the applicable maximum tariff rate, if applicable, and for the Primary Term originally set forth in the Releasing Shipper’s Firm Gas Transportation Agreement with Transporter. A Replacement Shipper who is awarded firm capacity pursuant to a Temporary Release shall execute a separate FTS or FTS-N Agreement for the
released capacity at the rate and for the term bid by the Replacement Shipper. A Replacement Shipper who is awarded firm capacity under a Temporary Release subject to recall shall execute a separate FTS or FTS-N Agreement for the released capacity, subject to the right of recall, at the rate and for the term bid by the Replacement Shipper. Unless the Releasing Shipper has agreed in the Offer to Release Firm Capacity, the Replacement Shipper must state in its FTS or FTS-N Agreement the same Primary Receipt or Delivery Points as the Releasing Shipper and cannot change those points. In addition, any rate discount provided the Releasing Shipper shall not be applicable to the Replacement Shipper under stated in Releasing Shipper’s Offer to Release Firm Capacity. As with the Releasing Shipper, any discounted rate for service on released capacity between particular Receipt and Delivery Points will not automatically transfer to service using other Receipt or Delivery Points at the discounted rate, unless Transporter directs the Replacement Shipper to use the other points for operational reasons, pursuant to Section 7 of the General Terms and Conditions.
12.12 Marketing Fees. Transporter may negotiate with a Releasing Shipper and receive a mutually agreeable fee for taking action to market Releasing Shipper’s firm capacity so long as such actions constitute more than merely posting the Offer to Release Firm Capacity. Transporter and the Releasing Shipper will negotiate the level of activity to be undertaken by Transporter to market the capacity and the fee to be paid by the Releasing Shipper to Transporter for such activity.
12.13 Offers to Purchase Firm Capacity. Transporter will post on Transporter’s Internet Website offers to purchase firm capacity currently available for release. Each offer must contain at least the name of the offeror, the amount of capacity in Dths per Day, the Receipt Points and the Delivery Points and the rate offered. Each offer will remain on Transporter’s Internet Website for thirty (30) days before it is removed, unless the party offering to purchase capacity notifies Transporter prior to the expiration of any thirty (30) days period that it wishes to extend the posting for an additional thirty (30) days or to remove the posting before the expiration of the thirty (30) days.
