RECORD 23 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE XIII. PREGRANTED ABANDONMENT AND RIGHT OF FIRST REFUSAL PROCEDURES
13.1 Applicability.
(a) Any Shipper receiving Firm Transportation Service under an FTS or FTS-N Agreement that has a Primary Term of one (1) year or more, that pays the applicable maximum tariff rate applicable to that service, and that does not have an evergreen provision in its Service Agreement, may exercise its right of first refusal in order to retain Firm Transportation Service at the expiration of the Primary Term as set forth in the particular Service Agreement.
(b) Any Shipper receiving Firm Transportation Service under an FTS or FTS-N Agreement that has a Primary Term of one (1) year or more, that pays the applicable maximum tariff rate applicable to that service, and that has an evergreen provision, may exercise its right of first refusal in order to retain continued firm transportation in the event that Transporter provides notice, as allowed by such Gas Transportation Agreement, that it will terminate the FTS or FTS-N Agreement at the expiration of the Primary Term or any Rollover Term.
(c) Any Shipper receiving transportation service provided under an FTS or FTS-N Agreement that has a Primary Term of less than one (1) Year or an ITS or ITS-N Agreement and that may or may not have an evergreen provision does not have the right of first refusal to retain its Interruptible or Firm Transportation Service at the expiration of a Primary Term or any subsequent roll-over term.
13.2 Posting of Capacity.
(a) At least ninety (90) Days prior to the effective termination date of an FTS or FTS-N Agreement with a Primary Term of one (1) year or more, whether such date is specified in the FTS or FTS-N Agreement or Transporter’s notice of termination as allowed by such FTS or FTS-N Agreement, Transporter shall post on its Internet Website the capacity that will be available upon the termination of a Shipper’s FTS or FTS-N Agreement and whether such capacity is subject to an existing Shipper’s right of first refusal. The capacity will be posted for not less than five (5) Business Days.
(b) The posting will include the Primary Receipt Points, the Primary Delivery Points, the available Firm MDQ, and Maximum Daily Quantity for each Primary Receipt and Delivery Point, the termination date of the FTS or FTS-N Agreement, and the applicable maximum tariff rate.
Bidding On Capacity. Upon posting of Available Capacity, Transporter shall receive bids in writing from eligible bidders who have executed a Gas Service Agreement. Bids must be submitted on Transporter’s “Bid for Released Firm Capacity” form posted on Transporter’s Internet Website as prescribed in Section 18 of these General Terms and Conditions and must be received by Transporter no later than 2:00 p.m. Central Clock Time on the Day of the bid deadline date. Transporter will post the relevant terms of all eligible bids, other than the bidder’s name, upon receipt of each bid received by Transporter. Transporter will determine the best bid in accordance with the Capacity Release provisions set forth in Section 12 of these General Terms and Conditions.
13.3 Right of First Refusal. If the right of first refusal applies, Transporter will notify an existing Shipper of the best bid, if any, received that Transporter is willing to accept. Shipper must provide Transporter written notification, which may be transmitted by facsimile transmission or other similar electronic means that it intends to exercise its right of first refusal. Shipper shall have a specified time, but not less than five (5) Business Days, within which Shipper must match the best bid. In order to match the best bid, Shipper must agree to pay a rate up to the applicable maximum tariff rate for an agreement term not to exceed five (5) years and that will provide Transporter at least the same net present value. If Shipper matches the best bid, Transporter and Shipper will enter into a new FTS or FTS-N Agreement or, in the sole discretion of Transporter, modify or amend the existing FTS or FTS-N Agreement to reflect the terms of the best bid. If Shipper fails to match the best bid within the time allowed by Transporter, Shipper’s existing FTS or FTS-N Agreement will be abandoned upon the termination of the Gas Transportation Agreement; and Transporter will enter into a new FTS or FTS-N Agreement with the Shippers offering the best acceptable bid. The highest rate that Shipper must match through the bidding process if it wishes to continue such service is the applicable maximum tariff rate.
13.4 Negotiated Rate. Shippers requesting service at a negotiated rate that exceeds the applicable maximum tariff rate will be considered to be paying the applicable maximum tariff rate for purposes of determining the economic value of requests for service rights.
13.5 Acceptable Bids. In the event Transporter does not receive any bids for Shipper’s capacity or any bids that are acceptable to Transporter, Shipper shall have the right to retain its firm capacity at the applicable maximum tariff rate or any rate mutually agreed upon between Transporter and Shipper for an additional term, subject to the terms and conditions applicable to such service as requested by Shipper. Absent an agreement on a mutually agreed upon rate between Transporter and Shipper, if Shipper refuses to renew its existing FTS or FTS-N Agreement at the applicable maximum tariff rate, such FTS-N Agreement shall be subject to abandonment upon its termination.
13.6 Abandonment. Transporter shall be relieved of its transportation service obligations for any FTS or FTS-N Agreement with a Primary Term of less than one (1) year, regardless of any subsequent Rollover Term provided in such FTS or FTS-N Agreement, and for any ITS or ITS-N Agreement upon the expiration or termination of such Service Agreement. Transporter shall be relieved of its transportation service obligations for any FTS or FTS-N Agreement with a Primary Term of one (1) year or more upon the expiration of such FTS or FTS-N Agreement, provided that Shipper gives notice to terminate its FTS or FTS- N Agreement pursuant to the provisions contained therein, or Shipper fails to match the best bid under its right of first refusal option as described in Section 13.4 of these General Terms and Conditions, or Shipper fails to submit a bid acceptable to Transporter.
13.7 Contractual Right of First Refusal. Transporter shall offer, on a not unduly discriminatory basis, a contractual right of first refusal to Shippers for an FTS or FTS-N Agreement that does not otherwise qualify for the regulatory right of first refusal set forth in this Section 13 of these General Terms and Conditions.

RECORD 24 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE XIV. GAS QUALITY
14.1 Quality Specifications. Gas delivered to Transporter at each Receipt Point under the Service Agreement must meet the quality specifications of the interstate pipeline from which Gas is delivered at each Receipt Point in accordance with each such pipeline’s then current published quality specifications. Otherwise, Transporter’s quality specifications require that all Gas delivered to Transporter at the each Receipt Point meet the following specifications:
(a) Objectionable Materials: The Gas shall be commercially free from dust, gum, gum-forming constituents, or other objectionable liquid or solid matter that might become separated from the Gas in the course of transmission through pipelines.
(b) Free Water and Liquid Hydrocarbons: Be delivered to the Receipt Points after standard mechanical separation by Shipper for the removal of free water and free liquid hydrocarbons.
(c) Vapor: The Gas shall be free of water at the temperature and pressure at which the Gas is delivered and shall not contain any hydrocarbons that might condense to free liquids in the pipeline under normal pipeline conditions; and in no event shall the Gas contain water vapor in excess of seven (7) pounds per one million (1,000,000) cubic feet, measured at fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia) at a standard temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F).
(d) Hydrogen Sulfide: The Gas shall not contain more than one-quarter (1/4) grains of hydrogen sulfide per one hundred (100) standard cubic feet as determined by quantitative methods in general use within the natural gas industry.
(e) Total Sulfur: The Gas shall not contain more than five (5) grains of total sulfur per one hundred (100) cubic feet (including mercaptans) as determined by quantitative methods in general use within the natural gas industry.
(f) Total Inerts (Carbon Dioxide and Nitrogen): The Gas shall not contain more than two percent (2%) by volume of carbon dioxide (CO2) and more than one percent (1%) by volume of nitrogen (N2).
(g) Oxygen: The Gas shall not contain more than two-tenths percent (.2%) by volume of oxygen (O2).
(h) Heavier Hydrocarbons: The gas shall not contain more than one and one-half percent (1.5%) by volume of heavier hydrocarbons (C4+).
(i) Non-Methane Hydrocarbons: The gas shall not contain more than twelve percent (12%) by volume of non-methane hydrocarbons (C2+).
Wobbe Number: The gas shall have a Wobbe Number of at least 1314 but no more than 1400. The Wobbe Number shall be calculated by dividing the Gross Heating Value (dry) of the gas (at
standard conditions 14.73 psia and 60 degrees Fahrenheit) by the square root of the specific gravity of the gas.
(j) Temperature: The Gas shall have a temperature of not less than forty degrees Fahrenheit (40° F) or more than one hundred and twenty degrees Fahrenheit (120° F).
(k) Gross Heating Value: The Gas shall contain a daily average heating content of not less than nine hundred sixty-seven (967) or greater than eleven hundred and ten (1110) Btu’s per cubic foot at 14.73 psia dry.
(m) Mercaptans: The Gas shall not contain more than one-quarter (1/4) grain of mercaptans per one hundred (100) standard cubic feet.
14.2 Receipt Point Non-Conformity. Should Shipper’s Gas at any Receipt Point not comply with the quality specifications of Section 14.1 of these General Terms and Conditions, Transporter shall immediately have the right to discontinue transportation of Gas from such Receipt Point and shall notify Shipper in writing of the quality specifications violation. Within forty-eight (48) hours thereafter, Shipper will be required to submit to Transporter a plan to conform such Gas to the quality specifications. If Shipper does not submit a plan and Shipper desires to continue to flow non-specification Gas, Transporter shall have the right, at its sole discretion, but not the obligation, to accept said non-specification Gas, provided that Transporter shall have the right to cease taking such non-specification Gas at any time or from time to time. If Shipper does not conform the non-specification Gas to the quality specifications and if Transporter does not accept said non-specification Gas, Transporter may terminate the Agreement, without any further liability to Shipper or any other entity in connection with such termination, upon thirty (30) days written notice to Shipper. If Transporter terminates the Agreement pursuant to the previous sentence, Shipper agrees that it will not execute a new Service Agreement with any other party at quality specifications equal to or more stringent than the foregoing. Shipper’s agreement in the previous sentence will survive the termination of the Service Agreement.
14.3 Non-Conforming Gas. If Shipper delivers Gas that does not meet the quality specifications set forth in Section 14.1 of these General Terms and Conditions, Shipper shall be liable to and shall indemnify and hold Transporter and any third party harmless from and against any Claims and Losses resulting therefrom.

RECORD 5 RATE SCHEDULE FTS FIRM TRANSPORTATION SERVICE
ARTICLE I. AVAILABILITY
1.1 This rate schedule is available to any Shipper for the firm transportation of gas by Transporter on Transporter’s Legacy System under the authority and provisions of Part 284 of FERC’s regulations, provided that:
(a) Transporter determines that it has sufficient capacity on that remaining part of its Legacy System to render the Firm Transportation Service and that it is able to provide said transportation;
(b) Any construction, repair, replacement, modification, acquisition, or expansion of facilities necessary to commence and provide the Firm Transportation Service has been completed;
(c) Shipper satisfies the creditworthiness criteria in accordance with Section 4 of the General Terms and Conditions; and,
(d) Shipper executes an FTS Agreement in the form contained in Record 60 of this FERC Gas Tariff.
ARTICLE II. APPLICABILITY AND CHARACTER OF SERVICE
2.1 Transportation hereunder, through all or any portion of the System, shall be firm from Primary Receipt Points to the Primary Delivery Points subject to the provisions of an FTS Agreement and to the General Terms and Conditions which are incorporated herein by reference.
2.2 Transportation hereunder shall consist of the acceptance by Transporter of gas nominated for the account of Shipper for transportation from the Primary Receipt Points specified in the FTS Agreement or Secondary Receipt Points as nominated by Shipper, the transportation of that gas through the System, and the delivery of Equivalent Quantities for the account of Shipper at the Primary Delivery Points specified in the FTS Agreement or Secondary Delivery Points as nominated by Shipper.
2.3 Transportation service provided under this rate schedule shall be limited to Shipper’s Firm MDQ specified in the FTS Agreement and Transporter shall not be obligated to provide transportation service hereunder in excess of the Firm MDQ so specified.
2.4 Transporter shall not be obligated to enter into an FTS Agreement at less than the applicable maximum tariff rate, as set forth in Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff, for service under this rate schedule.
2.5 Provided Transporter's prior consent, which shall not be unreasonably withheld, is obtained, Shipper may nominate quantities of gas in excess of the Firm MDQ specified in the FTS Agreement on any Day (an "Authorized Overrun") for receipt, transport, and delivery by Transporter of an Equivalent Quantity; provided, however, that the nomination and transportation of such gas can be accomplished by Transporter without detriment to any other Shipper under any of Transporter's Rate Schedules; and provided further that such Transportation is compatible to the operational requirements of Transporter's System. Subject to the foregoing restrictions, Transporter's consent shall not be unreasonably withheld.
The rate charged for such Authorized Overrun Quantities shall be in accordance with Article 3 of this Rate Schedule.
2.6 Transporter shall not be required to construct, repair, replace, modify, acquire, or expand any facilities in order to provide Transportation Service under this Rate Schedule FTS unless Transporter and Shipper agree to such in advance.
ARTICLE III. RATES AND CHARGES
3.1 Except, but only to the extent that, a Transporter and Shipper enter into a Service Agreement pursuant to Section 29 or Section 30 of the General Terms and Conditions applicable to this Rate Schedule, the applicable charges for Transportation provided under this rate schedule are set forth in the currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff. For all Transportation rendered under this rate schedule, Shipper shall pay Transporter each Month the sum of the Reservation Rate, Usage Rate, Authorized Overrun Charge, and any other charges as authorized under the provisions of this FERC Gas Tariff, as follows:
(a) Reservation Rate: An amount determined as the product of:
(i) The Shipper’s Firm MDQ specified in Exhibit B of the particular FTS Agreement; and
(ii) (a) The Monthly Reservation Rate per Dth set forth from time to time in the currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff; or
(b) The Daily Reservation per Dth set forth from time to time in the currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff times the number of Days in the Month during which Shipper has subscribed for FTS Transportation Service, as applicable.
(b) Usage Rate. An amount determined as the product of:
(i) The total quantity of gas in Dths delivered by Transporter for the account of Shipper during each Day the billing Month up to the Firm MDQ; and
(ii) The applicable Usage Rate per Dth set forth from time to time in the then currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff.
(c) Authorized Overrun Charge. An amount determined as the product of:
(i) The total quantity of gas in Dths delivered by Transporter for the account of Shipper on any Day during the billing Month in excess of Shipper’s Firm MDQ; and
(ii) The maximum ITS Usage Rate per Dth set forth from time to time in the then currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff.
(d) Other charges. Any other charges authorized from time to time under the provisions of this FERC Gas Tariff, including in accordance with Section 7 and Section 10 of the General Terms and Conditions and the applicable ACA unit charge as posted on the Commission’s website at www.ferc.gov <http://www.ferc.gov/> and set forth in Section 28 of the General Terms and Conditions. Unless Transporter agrees otherwise, in addition, Shipper shall pay Transporter for the cost of any facilities constructed, repaired, replaced, modified, acquired, or expanded in order for Transporter to provide Service for Shipper under and as set forth in the applicable FTS Agreement.
(e) Suspension of Reservation Rates.
(i) Force Majeure Condition. If Transporter is rendered unable, wholly or in part, by a Force Majeure Condition or because of the General Terms and Conditions of Transporter’s Tariff to perform its firm transportation obligations under any FTS Agreement for a period greater than ten (10) consecutive Days, then for each Day beyond such ten (10) consecutive Days that Transporter is rendered unable, wholly or in part, to so perform its firm transportation obligations under any such FTS Agreement to deliver Equivalent Quantities at Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points, Shipper shall be relieved of its obligation to pay the Reservation Rates under any such FTS Agreement applicable to that portion of the firm transportation service that is affected by the Force Majeure Condition or the condition under the General Terms and Conditions of Transporter’s Tariff, from and after the tenth (10th) Day of Transporter’s inability to perform its firm transportation obligations until the inability is corrected, but for no longer period. The suspension of Shipper’s obligation to pay the Reservation Rates shall be based on: (i) if Shipper was not provided with advance notice by Transporter prior to scheduling quantities for the period of such service outage, the nominated quantities which Transporter fails to deliver to Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points during any such outage period; and (ii) if Shipper was provided with advance notice by Transporter prior to scheduling quantities for the period of such service outage, the daily average quantities nominated by such Shipper for firm delivery at Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points during the seven (7) day period prior to the beginning of such Force Majeure Condition or effectiveness of the condition under the General Terms and Conditions of Transporter’s Tariff for each Day of Transporter’s failure to perform its firm transportation obligation. Shipper shall remain obligated to make payments for all or any portion of the Reservation Rates applicable to the firm transportation provided under a FTS Agreement when Transporter is capable, wholly or in part, of performing its firm transportation obligations and Transporter’s ability to perform such obligations is not affected by such Force Majeure Condition or because of the General Terms and Conditions of Transporter’s Tariff. Pipeline shall assess each Shipper receiving Firm Transportation Service that Shipper’s proportionate share of Reservation Rate charges for any period beyond ten (10) Days during which Transporter is incapable of performing all of its firm transportation obligations. The obligation to make payment for the Reservation Rate will not be suspended for Force Majeure Conditions that occur on the systems of third-parties (e.g., a Force Majeure Condition another shipper’s facilities or another pipeline’s facilities).
(ii) Non-Force Majeure Conditions. Except as otherwise provided in the General Terms and Conditions, if Transporter fails, wholly or in part, to perform its firm transportation obligations under an applicable FTS Agreement to deliver the Equivalent Quantities at Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points for reasons other than a Force Majeure Condition based on the quantity as Shipper has nominated, Shipper shall be relieved of its obligation to pay the Reservation Rates under the applicable FTS Agreement for Shipper’s nominated quantities of gas which Transporter was obligated, but was unable to deliver at Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points from the inception of Transporter’s failure to so perform its obligations under the applicable FTS Agreement until such failure is corrected, but for no longer period. The suspension of Shipper’s obligation to pay the Reservation Rates shall be based on : (i) if Customer was not provided with advance notice by Pipeline prior to scheduling quantities for the period of such service outage, the nominated quantities which Transporter fails to deliver to Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points during any such outage period; and (ii) if Customer was provided with advance notice by Pipeline prior to scheduling quantities for the period of such service outage, the suspension of Customer’s obligation to pay the Reservation Rates shall be based on the daily average quantities nominated by such Shipper for firm delivery at Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points during the seven (7) day period prior to the beginning of such pre-scheduled service outage, for each Day of Transporter’s failure to perform its firm transportation obligation.
(iii) No Suspension of Reservation Rate. No Reservation Rates shall be suspended to the extent that:
(A) Service is provided via a backhaul or exchange and Transporter’s interruption of service is necessitated by insufficient offsetting forward-haul service;
(B) Shipper fails to properly nominate in accordance with Section 6 of the General Terms and Conditions or otherwise fails to comply with its obligations under FTS Agreement or the General Terms and Conditions;
(C) Quantities are nominated from a Secondary Receipt Points or to Secondary Delivery Points;
(D) Transporter is able to restore service during the affected Day and Shipper fails to re-submit its Nomination in a later cycle;
(E) Unless otherwise provided for in a Negotiated Rate Agreement, Shipper is provided service pursuant to a Negotiated Rate Agreement;
(F) Service is interrupted due to Shipper’s recklessness, negligence, or misconduct;
(G) Service is interrupted solely because of the conduct or operations of an upstream Operator of Shipper’s Receipt Points or of a downstream Operator of Shipper’s Delivery Points or because of the failure of supply or the failure of any upstream or downstream transportation service which may affect Transporter’s firm transportation obligations;
(H) Service is interrupted solely as a result of Shipper’s refusal or inability to accept delivery of gas for which Transporter has its obligations in this FERC Gas Tariff; or
(I) New facilities designed in whole or in part to provide service to Shipper, are being installed, replaced, or modified.
ARTICLE IV. GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
4.1 This Rate Schedule and all of the General Terms and Conditions, including any future modifications, additions, or deletions, are applicable to Firm Transportation Service rendered under this Rate Schedule FTS and, by this reference, are incorporated herein and hereby made a part of this Rate Schedule FTS. If and to the extent that the provisions of this Rate Schedule FTS conflict with the provisions of the General Terms and Conditions, the provisions of this Rate Schedule FTS shall govern.

RECORD 6 RATE SCHEDULE FTS-N FIRM TRANSPORTATION SERVICE
ARTICLE I. AVAILABILITY
1.1 This rate schedule is available to any Shipper for the firm transportation of gas by Transporter under the authority and provisions of Part 284 of FERC’s regulations, provided that:
(a) Transporter determines that it has sufficient capacity to render the Firm Transportation Service and that it is able to provide said transportation;
(b) Any construction, repair, replacement, modification, acquisition, or expansion of facilities necessary to commence and provide the Firm Transportation Service has been completed;
(c) Shipper satisfies the creditworthiness criteria in accordance with Section 4 of the General Terms and Conditions; and,
(d) Shipper executes an FTS-N Agreement in the form contained in Record 60 of this FERC Gas Tariff.
ARTICLE II. APPLICABILITY AND CHARACTER OF SERVICE
2.1 Transportation hereunder, through all or any portion of the System, shall be firm from Primary Receipt Points to the Primary Delivery Points subject to the provisions of an FTS-N Agreement and to the General Terms and Conditions which are incorporated herein by reference.
2.2 Transportation hereunder shall consist of the acceptance by Transporter of gas nominated for the account of Shipper for transportation from the Primary Receipt Points specified in the FTS-N Agreement or Secondary Receipt Points as nominated by Shipper, the transportation of that gas through the System, and the delivery of Equivalent Quantities for the account of Shipper at the Primary Delivery Points specified in the FTS-N Agreement or Secondary Delivery Points as nominated by Shipper.
2.3 Transportation service provided under this rate schedule shall be limited to Shipper’s Firm MDQ specified in the FTS-N Agreement and Transporter shall not be obligated to provide transportation service hereunder in excess of the Firm MDQ so specified.
2.4 Transporter shall not be obligated to enter into an FTS-N Agreement at less than the applicable maximum tariff rate, as set forth in Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff, for service under this rate schedule.
Provided Transporter's prior consent, which shall not be unreasonably withheld, is obtained, Shipper may nominate quantities of gas in excess of the Firm MDQ specified in the FTS-N Agreement on any Day (an "Authorized Overrun") for receipt, transport, and delivery by Transporter of an Equivalent Quantity; provided, however, that the nomination and transportation of such gas can be accomplished by Transporter without detriment to any other Shipper under any of Transporter's Rate Schedules; and provided further that such Transportation is compatible to the operational requirements of Transporter's System. Subject to the foregoing restrictions, Transporter's consent shall not be unreasonably withheld.
The rate charged for such Authorized Overrun Quantities shall be in accordance with Article 3 of this Rate Schedule.
2.5 Transporter shall not be required to construct, repair, replace, modify, acquire, or expand any facilities in order to provide Transportation Service under this Rate Schedule FTS-N unless Transporter and Shipper agree to such in advance.
ARTICLE III. RATES AND CHARGES
3.1 Except, but only to the extent that, a Transporter and Shipper enter into a Service Agreement pursuant to Section 29 or Section 30 of the General Terms and Conditions applicable to this Rate Schedule, the applicable charges for Transportation provided under this rate schedule are set forth in the currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff. For all Transportation rendered under this rate schedule, Shipper shall pay Transporter each Month the sum of the Reservation Rate, Usage Rate, Authorized Overrun Charge, and any other charges as authorized under the provisions of this FERC Gas Tariff, as follows:
(a) Reservation Rate: An amount determined as the product of:
(i) The Shipper’s Firm MDQ specified in Exhibit B of the particular FTS-N Agreement; and
(ii) The Monthly Reservation Rate per Dth set forth from time to time in the currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff, or (b) the Daily Reservation per Dth set forth from time to time in the currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff times the number of Days in the Month during which Shipper has subscribed for FTS-N Transportation Service, as applicable.
(b) Usage Rate. An amount determined as the product of:
(i) The total quantity of gas in Dths delivered by Transporter for the account of Shipper during each Day the billing Month up to the Firm MDQ; and
(ii) The applicable Usage Rate per Dth set forth from time to time in the then currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff.
(c) Authorized Overrun Charge. An amount determined as the product of:
(i) The total quantity of gas in Dths delivered by Transporter for the account of Shipper on any Day during the billing Month in excess of Shipper’s Firm MDQ; and
(ii) The maximum ITS-N Usage Rate per Dth set forth from time to time in the then currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff.
(d) Other charges. Any other charges authorized from time to time under the provisions of this FERC Gas Tariff, including in accordance with Section 7 and Section 10 of the General Terms and Conditions and the applicable ACA unit charge as posted on the Commission’s website at www.ferc.gov <http://www.ferc.gov/> and set forth in Section 28 of the General Terms and Conditions. Unless Transporter agrees otherwise, in addition, Shipper shall pay Transporter for the cost of any facilities constructed, repaired, replaced, modified, acquired, or expanded in order for Transporter to provide Service for Shipper under and as set forth in the applicable FTS-N Agreement.
(e) Suspension of Reservation Rates.
(i) Force Majeure Condition. If Transporter is rendered unable, wholly or in part, by a Force Majeure Condition or because of the General Terms and Conditions of Transporter’s Tariff to perform its firm transportation obligations under any FTS-N Agreement for a period greater than ten (10) consecutive Days, then for each Day beyond such ten (10) consecutive Days that Transporter is rendered unable, wholly or in part, to so perform its firm transportation obligations under any such FTS-N Agreement to deliver Equivalent Quantities at Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points, Shipper shall be relieved of its obligation to pay the Reservation Rates under any such FTS-N Agreement applicable to that portion of the firm transportation service that is affected by the Force Majeure Condition or the condition under the General Terms and Conditions of Transporter’s Tariff, from and after the tenth (10th) Day of Transporter’s inability to perform its firm transportation obligations until the inability is corrected, but for no longer period. The suspension of Shipper’s obligation to pay the Reservation Rates shall be based on: (i) if Shipper was not provided with advance notice by Transporter prior to scheduling quantities for the period of such service outage, the nominated quantities which Transporter fails to deliver to Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points during any such outage period; and (ii) if Shipper was provided with advance notice by Transporter prior to scheduling quantities for the period of such service outage, the daily average quantities nominated by such Shipper for firm delivery at Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points during the seven (7) day period prior to the beginning of such Force Majeure Condition or effectiveness of the condition under the General Terms and Conditions of Transporter’s Tariff for each Day of Transporter’s failure to perform its firm transportation obligation. Shipper shall remain obligated to make payments for all or any portion of the Reservation Rates applicable to the firm transportation provided under a FTS-N Agreement when Transporter is capable, wholly or in part, of performing its firm transportation obligations and Transporter’s ability to perform such obligations is not affected by such Force Majeure Condition or because of the General Terms and Conditions of Transporter’s Tariff. Pipeline shall assess each Shipper receiving Firm Transportation Service that Shipper’s proportionate share of Reservation Rate charges for any period beyond ten (10) Days during which Transporter is incapable of performing all of its firm transportation obligations. The obligation to make payment for the Reservation Rate will not be suspended for Force Majeure Conditions that occur on the systems of third-parties (e.g., a Force Majeure Condition another shipper’s facilities or another pipeline’s facilities).
Non-Force Majeure Conditions. Except as otherwise provided in the General Terms and Conditions, if Transporter fails, wholly or in part, to perform its firm transportation obligations under an applicable FTS-N Agreement to deliver the Equivalent Quantities at Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points for reasons other than a Force Majeure Condition based on the quantity as Shipper has nominated, Shipper shall be relieved of its obligation to pay the Reservation Rates under the applicable FTS-N Agreement for Shipper’s nominated quantities of gas which Transporter was obligated, but was unable to deliver at Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points from the inception of Transporter’s failure
to so perform its obligations under the applicable FTS-N Agreement until such failure is corrected, but for no longer period. The suspension of Shipper’s obligation to pay the Reservation Rates shall be based on: (i) if Customer was not provided with advance notice by Pipeline prior to scheduling quantities for the period of such service outage, the nominated quantities which Transporter fails to deliver to Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points during any such outage period; and (ii) if Customer was provided with advance notice by Pipeline prior to scheduling quantities for the period of such service outage, the suspension of Customer’s obligation to pay the Reservation Rates shall be based on the daily average quantities nominated by such Shipper for firm delivery at Shipper’s Primary Delivery Points during the seven (7) day period prior to the beginning of such pre-scheduled service outage, for each Day of Transporter’s failure to perform its firm transportation obligation.
(ii) No Suspension of Reservation Rate. No Reservation Rates shall be suspended to the extent that:
(A) Service is provided via a backhaul or exchange and Transporter’s interruption of service is necessitated by insufficient offsetting forward-haul service;
(B) Shipper fails to properly nominate in accordance with Section 6 of the General Terms and Conditions or otherwise fails to comply with its obligations under FTS-N Agreement or the General Terms and Conditions;
(C) Quantities are nominated from a Secondary Receipt Points or to Secondary Delivery Points;
(D) Transporter is able to restore service during the affected Day and Shipper fails to re-submit its Nomination in a later cycle;
(E) Unless otherwise provided for in a Negotiated Rate Agreement, Shipper is provided service pursuant to a Negotiated Rate Agreement;
(F) Service is interrupted due to Shipper’s recklessness, negligence, or misconduct;
(G) Service is interrupted solely because of the conduct or operations of an upstream Operator of Shipper’s Receipt Points or of a downstream Operator of Shipper’s Delivery Points or because of the failure of supply or the failure of any upstream or downstream transportation service which may affect Transporter’s firm transportation obligations;
(H) Service is interrupted solely as a result of Shipper’s refusal or inability to accept delivery of gas for which Transporter has its obligations in this FERC Gas Tariff; or
New facilities, designed in whole or in part to provide service to Shipper, are being installed, replaced, or modified.
ARTICLE IV. GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS

RECORD 11 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE I. DEFINITIONS: 1.1 The following terms, when used in this FERC Gas Tariff or in any Service Agreement executed for service under a rate schedule contained in this FERC Gas Tariff, shall have the following meanings:
(a) “Agent” means a third party authorized to act for a Shipper and that has executed an Agency Agreement set forth on Transporter’s Internet Website.
(b) “Agency Agreement” means the agreement as set forth on Transporter’s Internet Website which is to be used by a Shipper to designate a third party as an agent for a Shipper.
(c) “Anchor Shipper” means those shippers identified in the Stipulation and Agreement filed by Transporter at the FERC on December 12, 2014 in Docket No. CP14-125, et al. and which are identified in Section 35 of these General Terms and Conditions.
(d) “Applicable Laws” means any law, rule, regulation, order, obligation, requirement, responsibility, code, ordinance, or rule of conduct or procedure enacted, issued, or required by a governmental or quasi-governmental authority that is applicable to any party or transaction which is made or entered into pursuant to this FERC Gas Tariff.
(e) “Available Capacity” means the quantitative ability of the System to provide gas transportation service up to its certificated quantity. The ability of the System to provide gas transportation service may be limited by changes in prevailing operating pressures, temperatures, gas flow rates, and gas flow directions within any portions of the System, including any Receipt Points or any Delivery Points; physical capacity limitations of compressors, regulators, valves, pipelines, measuring facilities, or appurtenances to the System; or necessary testing, maintenance, repair, overhaul, alteration, modification, replacement, enlargement, or construction of pipelines, compressors, metering, regulating, or other facilities or equipment appurtenant to the System.
(f) “Authorized Overrun” means a delivery by Transporter for Shipper that on any Day is in excess of a Shipper’s Firm MDQ or Interruptible MDQ for that Day that has been accepted, confirmed, and scheduled by Transporter.
(g) “Btu” means a British thermal unit measured at a pressure of 14.73 psia at 60 degrees Fahrenheit (60° F). The standard Btu is the International Btu, which is also called the Btu (IT).
“Bump” means the displacement of a scheduled interruptible service during the evening or Intra-day 1 nomination cycle resulting from the scheduling of increased firm service nominations during a cycle.
(h) “Business Day” means Monday through Friday, excluding Federal banking holidays for transactions in the U.S., and similar holidays for transactions occurring in Canada and Mexico.
(i) “Cash-Out Price” means a price calculated by Transporter that will be applied to monthly imbalances. Transporter will determine the Cash-Out Price by utilizing the published cash out price for each Upstream Pipeline that delivers gas to Transporter through any Receipt Point on Transporter’s System in accordance with the cash out price procedures under the currently effective tariff or other similar agreement of each such upstream pipeline. The “Cash-Out Price” on Transporter’s System shall be the weighted average price determined by calculating a supply percentage for each Upstream Pipeline delivering gas to Transporter based upon the amount of gas nominated by the Shipper and scheduled by Transporter at each Upstream Pipeline Receipt Point times the cash-out price or similar value used by each such Upstream Pipeline for cashing-out imbalances, before adjustments, of each Upstream Pipeline.
(j) “Central Clock Time” of “CCT” means Central Time, adjusted for standard and daylight savings time. Any reference to Central Time is Central Clock Time.
(k) “Claims” means all claims, damages, and Losses of whatever nature, including contractually-assumed, liens, court or arbiter awards, negotiated settlements, and all costs and expenses related to all of the above including reasonable attorneys’ and experts fees.
(l) “Confirmation Requester” means a service provider (including a point operator) that is seeking to confirm a quantity of gas via the information outlined in NAESB Standard 1.4.3 with another service provider (the Confirming Party) with respect to a nomination at a location.
(m) “Confirming Party” means a service provider (including a point operator) that provides a confirmation for a quantity of gas via the information outlined in NAESB WGQ Standard No. 1.4.4 to another service provider (the Confirmation Requester) with respect to a nomination at a location.
(n) “Critical Day” means a Day when a Critical Notice has been posted on Transporter’s Internet Website.
(o) “Critical Notice” means the issuance of an Immediate Action Critical Notice, posting of an Imbalance OFO or posting of a Critical Day OFO under Section 7 of these General Terms and Conditions of Service. Critical Notices will be posted separately on Transporter’s Internet Website.

RECORD 12 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE ll. OPERATING PROVISIONS FOR FIRM TRANSPORTATION SERVICE (RATE SCHEDULES FTS & FTS-N)
2.1 Availability of Firm Service. Firm service under this FERC Gas Tariff shall be provided when and to the extent that Transporter determines that capacity is available on the System, which capacity is not subject to a superior claim by another Shipper. Existing uncommitted firm capacity will be posted on Transporter’s Internet Website and will be made available in accordance with the provisions of Section 2.2 of these General Terms and Conditions.
2.2 Shipper Requests for Firm Service. Requests for firm service hereunder shall be made by providing the specific information in Section 5 of these General Terms and Conditions. Request for Service forms shall be submitted to Transporter at the address shown in the Firm Service Agreement form in Record 60 or Record 61. Transporter shall consider all complete requests in the order received and will notify Shipper in writing of the acceptance of a complete request.
2.3 Receipt and Delivery Point Designations. Each Receipt Point and Delivery Point specified by a Shipper requesting Firm Transportation Service shall be considered as Primary Receipt Points and Primary Delivery Points for Firm Transportation Service under either an FTS or FTS-N Agreement. Unless otherwise agreed, each Shipper’s Firm MDQ must be allocated among the Primary Receipt Points such that the Firm MDQ equals the sum of the individual maximum daily quantities for Primary Receipt Points as well as the Maximum Daily Quantity for the Primary Delivery Points.
2.4 Changes to Receipt Point Designations. A Shipper may amend its FTS or FTS-N Agreement to add Primary Receipt Points, delete Primary Receipt Points, or modify Primary Receipt Points up to the maximum capacity of each such Receipt Point provided capacity is available to provide firm service at such points. A Shipper may change Primary Receipt Points upon twenty-four (24) hours’ notice, provided such capacity is posted as available on the Internet Website. If such capacity is not posted as available, Shipper may change Primary Receipt Points upon not more than five (5) Days’ notice provided Transporter determines that capacity is available to accommodate the requested change.
Unless otherwise agreed, the Firm MDQ must be allocated such that the Firm MDQ, as adjusted for appropriate reductions, equals the sum of the individual maximum daily quantities for each Primary Receipt Point.
Secondary Points. All System points, including Primary Receipt Points where capacity exists in excess of capacity allocated to provide Primary Receipt Point under a Firm Agreement, will be available for scheduling as Secondary Receipt Points. Transporter shall not limit the number of Primary and Secondary Receipt Points that a firm Shipper may request to utilize as long as the sum of nominated volumes at Shipper’s Primary and Secondary Receipt Points does not exceed Shipper’s Firm MDQ. Any discounted rate for Firm Transportation Service between Primary Receipt and Delivery Points will not automatically transfer to Service using Secondary Receipt or Delivery Points at the discounted rate and the applicable maximum rate set forth in Record 4 of this Gas Tariff shall be applicable unless Transporter, pursuant to Section 7 of these General Terms and Conditions, directs Shipper to use a Secondary Receipt or Delivery Point for operational reasons.
2.5 Requests for Operating Data. Upon request by Transporter, Shipper shall submit estimates of daily, monthly, and annual quantities of gas to be transported, including peak day requirements, together with the estimated amounts thereof applicable to each Primary Receipt Point and Primary Delivery Point. Transporter shall use such information and operating data to determine the System’s Available Capacity, to evaluate potential System capacity needs, to plan its maintenance and repair operations, or to assure adequate service to its Shippers.
2.6 Available Capacity. Transporter will make capacity available for Firm Transportation Service to the extent that Transporter determines it is operationally feasible. If operating conditions ever limit Transporter’s ability to provide Firm Transportation Service, then Transporter shall provide such service on the basis described in Section 7 of these General Terms and Conditions.
2.7 Uniform Hourly Deliveries. The Gas shall be delivered and redelivered as nearly as practicable at uniform hourly and daily rates of flow. Unless a different hourly rate is agreed to and otherwise provided for in the FTS-N Agreement, Transporter shall not be obligated to receive or deliver more than 1/24th of Shipper’s total Firm MDQ during any hour.
2.8 Additional Facilities. Transporter shall not be required to repair, construct, modify, replace, expand, or acquire facilities to provide Firm Transportation Service unless Transporter and Shipper mutually agree to such and the terms and conditions under which such will be conducted.

RECORD 13 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE lll. OPERATING PROVISIONS FOR INTERRUPTIBLE TRANSPORTATION SERVICE (RATE SCHEDULE ITS & ITS-N)
3.1 Availability of Interruptible Transportation Service. Interruptible Transportation Service under this FERC Gas Tariff shall be provided when, and to the extent that Transporter determines that capacity is available on the System, which capacity is not subject to a prior claim by another Shipper. Available interruptible capacity shall be allocated by Transporter by rate; the interruptible service priority shall be determined in accordance with Section 7 of these General Terms and Conditions.
3.2 Shipper Requests for Transportation Interruptible Service. Requests for Interruptible Transportation Service hereunder shall be made by providing the specific information in Section 5 of these General Terms and Conditions. Request for Service forms shall be submitted to Transporter at the address shown in the ITS or ITS-N Service Agreement form in Record 62 or Record 63. Transporter shall consider all complete requests in the order received and will notify Shipper in writing of the acceptance of a complete request.
3.3 Request Invalidation. Requests for Interruptible Transportation Service under this FERC Gas Tariff will be invalid and will not be considered if Service is requested to commence later than six (6) Months after the information specified in Section 5 of these General Terms and Conditions is provided to Transporter.
3.4 Execution of ITS or ITS-N Agreement. Shipper must execute an ITS or ITS-N Agreement in the form contained in this FERC Gas Tariff within thirty (30) days from the date Transporter nominates an ITS or ITS- N Agreement for execution, but in no event subsequent to commencement of Service. If a Shipper fails to execute an ITS or ITS-N Agreement within thirty (30) days, the request for Interruptible Transportation Service shall be deemed a nullity for all present and future purposes. Any discounted rate for Interruptible Transportation Service between particular Receipt and Delivery Points will not automatically transfer to service using other Receipt or Delivery Points at the discounted rate unless Transporter directs Shipper to use the other points for operational reasons pursuant to Section 7 of these General Terms and Conditions.
3.5 Requests for Operating Data. Upon request of Transporter, Shipper shall submit estimates of daily, monthly, and annual quantities of gas to be transported, including peak day requirements, together with the estimated amounts thereof applicable to each Receipt Point and Delivery Point. Transporter shall use such information and operating data to determine to the extent practicable the System’s Available Capacity, to evaluate potential System capacity needs, to plan its maintenance and repair operations, or to assure adequate service to its Shippers.
3.6 Receipt and Delivery Points. Each Receipt Point and the Delivery Point on the System is available for Interruptible Transportation Service subject to the allocation of capacity at such points first to Firm Transportation Service and second to Interruptible Transportation Service with a higher priority in accordance with Section 7.1 of these General Terms and Conditions. Subject to the availability of capacity, on an interruptible basis, a Shipper may utilize any Receipt Point or Delivery Point up to the lesser of the daily transportation quantities at each Receipt Point or Delivery Point or the Interruptible MDQ set forth in its ITS or ITS-N Agreement. All Receipt Points, as changed from time to time, shall be deemed to be included in all ITS and ITS-N Agreements.
Interruption of Service. Transporter retains all rights at any and all times during the term of an ITS or ITS- N Agreement to decrease or temporarily suspend receipt or delivery of gas if such capacity is required to
render service of a higher priority. If Transporter exercises such rights, Shipper shall Indemnify Transporter from any Loss or Claim that such Shipper or other party may incur by reason of such decrease or suspension.
3.7 Failure to Use Service. If within three (3) Months after the execution of an ITS or ITS-N Agreement Shipper has not commenced service under the provisions of such ITS or ITS-N Agreement or, if Shipper has commenced service but fails to use service during a consecutive twelve (12) Month period after commencement, Transporter may, on a non-discriminatory basis, terminate the ITS or ITS-N Agreement and Shipper’s request for Interruptible Transportation Service shall be deemed a nullity for all present and future purposes. Transporter shall give Shipper written notice thirty (30) days in advance of termination of an ITS or ITS-N Agreement. Shipper may retain the ITS or ITS-N Agreement by notifying Transporter in writing of its intent to retain such ITS or ITS-N Agreement; provided, however, if Shipper fails to use Interruptible Transportation Service during a consecutive twelve (12) Month period after notice of its intent to retain such service, the ITS or ITS-N Agreement and Shipper’s request for Interruptible Transportation Service shall be automatically terminated and abandoned.
3.8 Overbooking of Available Capacity. Transporter may contract to transport gas, on an interruptible basis, in excess of Available Capacity. If such overbooking should ever limit Transporter’s ability to provide Interruptible Transportation Service, then Transporter shall provide such service on the basis described in Section 7 of these General Terms and Conditions.
3.9 Uniform Hourly Deliveries. The Gas shall be delivered and redelivered as nearly as practicable at uniform hourly and daily rates of flow. Transporter shall not be obligated to receive or deliver more than 1/24th of Shipper’s scheduled quantities during any hour during any Day.
3.10 Additional Facilities. Transporter shall not be required to repair, construct, modify, replace, expand, or acquire facilities to provide Interruptible Transportation Service unless Transporter and Shipper mutually agree to such and the terms and conditions under which such will be conducted.

(i) The total quantity of gas in Dths delivered by Transporter for the account of Shipper during the billing Month; and
(ii) The ITS Usage Rate per Dth set forth from time to time in the then currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff.

(i) The total quantity of gas in Dths delivered by Transporter for the account of Shipper on and Day during the billing Month in excess of Shipper’s Interruptible MDQ; and
(ii) Whether or not the transportation of Shipper’s gas is discounted, the maximum ITS Usage Rate per Dth set forth from time to time in the then currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff.

4.1 This Rate Schedule ITS and all of the General Terms and Conditions, including any future modifications, additions, or deletions, are applicable to interruptible transportation service rendered under this Rate Schedule ITS and, by this reference, are incorporated and hereby made a part of this Rate Schedule ITS. 23.2 Notification. 22.6 Ancillary Equipment. Transporter shall not be required to perform service under any Rate Schedules which are a part of Transporter's FERC Gas Tariff unless all facilities necessary to provide the requested service exist and are in good operating condition.
22.7 Emergency Actions. Transporter shall be authorized to use all system resources, to maintain operational control of its system in the event Transporter in its reasonable discretion determines that system integrity is imminently threatened, even if the utilization of such resources results in the diversion of Gas. The Shipper whose actions resulted in the need to divert Gas shall Indemnify Transporter from and against any and all Claims of every kind and character which Transporter or Shippers may suffer, sustain, or be liable for, and shall Indemnify Transporter from and against any and all Claims whatsoever threatened or initiated as a result of the Gas diversion. Transporter shall have no responsibility to purchase Gas in situations resulting in the diversion of Gas for operational needs; provided, however, a Shipper whose Gas was diverted pursuant to this Section 22.7 of General Terms and Condition shall be compensated by Transporter at the Cash-Out Index Price utilized for cash-out of imbalances during the Month. In the event a Gas diversion results from the actions of a Shipper, such Shipper shall be responsible for compensating Transporter to the extent Transporter has compensated the Shipper whose Gas was diverted. RECORD 41 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE XXXI. FUEL, LOST AND UNACCOUNTED FOR GAS
31.1 Purpose. This Section 31 of these General Terms and Conditions describes how Transporter shall update annually the FL&A.
31.2 Procedures. The FL&A set out in Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff will be updated annually. Transporter will make a filing (with workpapers) with FERC March 1 of each Year setting forth the updated FL&A to be effective April 1 through March 31 of the following year. This updated FL&A will be based upon the actual data for previous calendar Year (“Base Period”). When this FERC Gas Tariff becomes effective, the FL&A will be one and one-half percent (1.5%) for service under Rate Schedules FTS and ITS and one-half percent (0.5%) for service under Rate Schedules FTS-N and ITS-N.
31.3 Calculation for Unaccounted for Gas Retention Percentage. The FL&A shall be determined by dividing the sum of Sections 31.3(a) through 31.3(d) of these General Terms and Conditions as described below:
(a) The actual quantity of Fuel, Lost and Unaccounted for Gas for the applicable Base Period, plus,
(b) Over-recovery (as a negative value) or under-recovery (as a positive value) amount associated with Transporter’s transmission facilities during the Base Period, plus,
(c) Any amount credited (negative if net over-recovery or positive if net under-recovery of cash-out revenue) pursuant to Section 10.5 of these General Terms and Condition, divided by,
(d) The amount in Section 31.3(a) of these General Terms and Conditions plus the applicable quantity of gas delivered by Transporter during the Base Period.
31.4 Over and under Recovery. The over-recovery or under-recovery amount during the Base Period shall be calculated as the difference between Sections 31.4(a) and 31.4(b) of these General Terms and Conditions, as follows:
(a) The quantity of Gas retained by Transporter under the applicable rate schedules during the Base Period plus the over-recovery amount (will be in addition to the quantity of gas retained) or under-recovery amount (will be a subtraction to the quantity of gas retained) for the prior year Base Period (prior year Base Period over-recovery or under-recovery amount will be zero for the initial filing) and
(b) The actual quantity of Fuel, Lost and Unaccounted for Gas during the Base Period; provided, however, the FL&A shall not be less than 0.0%.
31.5 Waiver of Fuel Charge. Transporter may waive charging a Shipper that portion of the FL&A constituting Transporter’s use gas for any transaction whose path does not actually involve Transporter’s use of gas. The paths for which this portion of the FL&A is not applied shall be posted on Transporter’s Internet Website.

RECORD 37 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE XXVII. CREDITING MECHANISM FOR PENALTY REVENUES AND CASH-OUT DIFFERENTIALS
The purpose of this provision is to provide the method by which Transporter will return penalty revenues or cash- out differentials, as defined herein, to Shippers.
27.1 Definitions: the following terms shall have the designated meaning:
(a) “Penalty Revenues” shall mean the total revenues collected by Transporter during a calendar Year, net of Transporter’s administrative costs, for any of the following:
(i) Penalties assessed pursuant to Sections 7.4 and 7.5 of the General Terms and Conditions; plus
(ii) Penalties assessed pursuant to Section 8 of these General Terms and Conditions; less
(iii) Penalties imposed upon Transporter by an Upstream Pipeline or downstream pipeline in accordance with Section 7.4 of the General Terms and Conditions or otherwise.
(iv) Penalties assessed pursuant to Section 22.7 of these General Terms and Conditions.
(b) “Cash-Out Differentials” shall mean the revenues collected by Transporter, less all costs, during a calendar Year pursuant to the tiered cash-out schedule in Section 10.3 of the General Terms and Conditions to the extent such net revenues are not used in the FL&A calculation as authorized in Section 10.5 of these General Terms and Conditions.
27.2 Methodology.
(a) Penalty Revenues or Cash-Out Differentials will be returned to Shippers on or before March 31 of each Year following the calendar Year of collection.
(b) Shippers will not be eligible to receive a portion of the Penalty Revenues or Cash-Out Differentials for the Months where they are penalized.
(c) Transporter will calculate a Shipper’s allocation of the Penalty Revenues or Cash-Out Differentials using the Shipper’s actual accumulated throughput in the Months that a Shipper was eligible, as a percentage of the total eligible accumulated throughput of all Shippers for the calendar Year.
(d) If during the applicable calendar Year, Transporter pays out more amounts than it receives, the amounts paid in such calendar Year will be offset against any accumulated amounts during the subsequent calendar Years.

RECORD 40 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE XXX. NEGOTIATED RATES
30.1 Negotiated Rate Agreement; Requirements. Shipper and Transporter may agree to a negotiated rate with respect to the rates, charges, and surcharges identified in a rate schedule that may be less than, equal to, or greater than the applicable maximum tariff rate for service under the applicable rate schedule. Such negotiated rate shall not be less than the minimum rate for service under the applicable rate schedule; may be based on rate design other than straight fixed variable; and may include a minimum quantity, production dedication, or other form of consideration. Such negotiated rate shall be set forth in an exhibit in the Service Agreement and shall be filed with FERC as required by FERC’s regulations. The applicable maximum tariff rate for service under a rate schedule shall be available to any Shipper that does not choose a negotiated rate. Any negotiated rate shall only be applicable for the period agreed upon between Transporter and Shipper. At the end of such period, the otherwise applicable maximum tariff rates or charges shall govern the service provided to Shipper hereunder.
30.2 Negotiated Rate May Exceed Maximum Rate; Exception. Shippers paying a negotiated rate that exceeds the applicable maximum tariff rate for service under a rate schedule will be considered to be paying the applicable maximum tariff rate for service under such rate schedule for purposes of scheduling, curtailment, and interruption, and calculating the economic value of a request for unsubscribed firm capacity. Replacement Shippers may not bid or pay a rate greater than the applicable maximum tariff rate for service under the Rate Schedules FTS or FTS-N and are not eligible for negotiated rates for the FTS or FTS-N Agreement.
30.3 Other Payment and Crediting Options. Transporter and Shipper may agree hereunder to a Negotiated Rate which includes payment obligations or crediting mechanisms in the event of a capacity release which vary from those set out in Section 12 of the General Terms and Conditions. Nothing in the foregoing sentence, however, shall authorize Transporter or Shipper to violate the FERC's policy with respect to the negotiation of terms and conditions of service.
30.4 Allocation of Costs and Revenues. The allocation of costs to and the recording of revenues from, service at Negotiated Rates will follow Transporter's normal practices associated with all of its services under this FERC Gas Tariff. Transporter will maintain separate records of Negotiated Rate transactions for each billing period. These records shall include the volumes transported, the billing determinants, the rates charged and the revenue received associated with such transactions.
30.5 Discount Rate Adjustments. A discount-type adjustment to rates for negotiated rate agreements shall only be allowed to the extent that Transporter can meet the standards required of an affiliate discount- type adjustment including requiring that Transporter shall have the burden of proving that any discount granted is required to meet competition. Transporter shall be required to demonstrate that any discount- type adjustment for negotiated rate agreements does not have an adverse impact on recourse rate shippers.
Demonstrating that, in the absence of Transporter's entering into such negotiated rate agreement providing for such discount, Transporter would not have been able to contract for such capacity at any higher rate, and that recourse rates would otherwise be as high or higher than recourse rates which result after applying the discount adjustment; or
(a) Making another comparable showing that the negotiated rate discount contributes more fixed costs to the System than could have been achieved without the discount.

BBT (Midla), LLC Record 39 FERC Gas Tariff GT&C (Discounted Rates) Eight Revised Volume No. 1 Version 1.0.0 ___________________________________________________________________________________ RECORD 39 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE XXIX. DISCOUNTED RATES
29.1 General. On a not unduly discriminatory basis, Transporter may charge a Shipper for service under the applicable Rate Schedule a rate, charge, or surcharge that is less than the applicable maximum tariff rate set forth from time to time in the currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff; provided, that such rates, charges, or surcharge may not be less than the applicable minimum rate set forth from time to time in the currently effective Record 4 of this FERC Gas Tariff. Any discount granted hereunder shall only be applicable for the period agreed upon by Transporter. At the end of such period, the otherwise applicable maximum tariff rates and charges shall govern the service provided to Shipper hereunder. Transporter shall file with FERC any and all reports or post information on its Internet Website as required by FERC’s regulations setting forth the applicable discounted rates and Shippers affected along with any other information that may be required.
29.2 Order of Discounting. In the event Transporter provides a discount to a Shipper, Transporter shall discount the components of the total rate in the following order:
(a) Reservation Rate; and
(b) Usage Rate.
29.3 Discount Terms. In the event that Transporter agrees to discount its rate to Shipper below the applicable maximum tariff rate, the following discount terms may be reflected on the applicable Service Agreement and will apply without the discount constituting a material deviation from Transporter’s applicable pro forma Service Agreements; provided, however, that any such discounted rates set forth below shall be between the minimum and maximum rates applicable to the service provided under the applicable Rate Schedule. Transporter and Shipper may agree that a specified discounted rate will apply under the following conditions:
(a) To specified quantities under Shipper’s Service Agreements;
(b) To specified quantities above or below a certain level or all quantities if quantities exceed a certain level;
(c) In a specified relationship to quantities actually transported (i.e., that the Reservation Rate will be adjusted in a specified relationship to quantities actually transported);
(d) To specified quantities during specified periods of time or during specified periods of the Year;
(e) To specified quantities at specific Receipt Points or Delivery Points; or
That a specific discounted rate is based on published index prices for specific Receipt Points or Delivery Points or other agreed-upon published pricing reference points (such discounted rate may be based upon the differential between published prices or arrived at by formula). Any agreement containing such discounted rate shall specify the rate components to be discounted (i.e., Reservation Rate, Usage Rate, or both), and any formula will provide a Reservation Rate per unit of contract demand.
29.4 Conditions of Index Price Differential Discount. To the extent the Reservation Rate is discounted, the index price differential rate formula shall be calculated to state a rate per Dth. Furthermore, such discount shall not change the underlying rate design of the service being provided or include any minimum bill or maximum take provision that would have the effect of guaranteeing revenue.
29.5 Adjustments to Discounted Rates. In addition, the discount agreement may include a provision that if one rate component which was at or below the applicable maximum tariff rate at the time the discount agreement was executed subsequently exceeds the applicable maximum tariff rate or is less than the applicable minimum tariff rate due to a change in Transporter’s maximum or minimum recourse rates so that such rate component must be adjusted downward or upward to equal the new applicable maximum (minimum) rate, the other rate components may be adjusted upward or downward to achieve the agreed overall rate, so long as none of the resulting rate components exceed the applicable maximum recourse rate or are less than the applicable minimum recourse rate applicable to that rate component. Such changes to rate components shall be applied prospectively commencing with the date a FERC order accepts revised tariff sheets. Nothing contained herein shall be construed to alter a refund obligation under applicable law for any period during which rates which had been charged under a discount agreement exceeded rates which ultimately are found to be just and reasonable.
