RECORD 16 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
ARTICLE VI. NOMINATION AND CONFIRMATION PROCEDURES
6.1 Required Information.
(a) Shipper shall nominate gas by notifying Transporter of the daily quantity of gas in Dths it has available at the Receipt Points and of the quantity of gas it desires to have delivered at the Delivery Points. The total volumes to be delivered for the account of Shipper by Transporter must equal the total receipt nominations plus FL&A if applicable and any other adjustments provided in the definition of Equivalent Quantities.
(b) All nominations should include Shipper-defined begin dates and end dates. All nominations should have roll-over options. Specifically, Shippers should have the ability to nominate for several Days, Months, or Years, provided the nomination begin and end dates are within the term of the Shipper's contract.
6.2 Calculation of Time. All times listed in this Section 6 of these General Terms and Conditions are Central Clock Time.
6.3 Form of Nomination. Nominations must be submitted in writing via the Internet Website or EDI and must include the information specified in Section 6.1 of these General Terms and Conditions, and the information required in a "Nomination" as defined in Section 1 of these General Terms and Conditions.
6.4 Staffing. Transporter will support a seven-day-a-week, twenty-four-hour-a-day nominations process. Transporter's personnel may not be at Transporter's office, but will be available by telephone, email, or other electronic means.
6.5 Nomination Cycles.
(a) A Shipper may avail itself of five nomination cycles: Timely; Evening; Intra-day 1; Intra-day 2; and Intra-day 3. Transporter will determine the applicable nomination processing cycle based upon the receipt time and beginning effective Day of the nomination. Where Transporter supports the processing of beginning effective time, Transporter will also use the beginning effective date and time in determining the applicable nomination processing cycle in lieu of using the nomination's receipt date and time to determine the processing cycle. Transporter will make an end of the Day scheduled quantity document available to Shippers, but a Shipper may waive Transporter's obligation to send this information. The nomination cycles and timelines provided in this Section 6 of these General Terms and Conditions shall apply to Shippers and Title Transfer Tracking service providers.
(b) Nominations received after nomination deadline should be scheduled after the nominations received before the nominations deadline.
(c) With respect to General Terms and Conditions Sections 6.7 through 6.10, for purposes of NAESB WGQ Standard No. 1.3.2 (ii), (iii), (iv), and (v), "provides" shall mean, for transmittals pursuant to NAESB WGQ Standards 1.4.x, receipt at the Designated Site, and for purposes of other forms of transmittal, it shall mean send or post.
6.6 Timely Nomination Cycle:
Nominations must leave the control of the nominating party by 1:00 p.m.
(a) Nominations must be received by Transporter by 1:15 p.m. (including from Title Transfer Tracking service providers).
(b) Transporter will send a Quick Response by 1:30 p.m.
(c) Upstream and downstream connected parties must confirm with Transporter no later than -4:30 p.m.
(d) Shippers and point operators must receive scheduled quantities by 5:00 p.m. on the Day prior to flow.
(e) Scheduled quantities resulting from a Timely Nomination will be effective at 9:00 a.m. on the gas Day.
(f) Transporter reserves the right to waive the nomination deadline on a nondiscriminatory basis.
6.7 Evening Nomination Cycle:
(a) Nominations must leave the control of the nominating party by 6:00 p.m.
(b) Nominations must be received by Transporter by 6:15 p.m. (including from Title Transfer Tracking service providers).
(c) Transporter will send a Quick Response by 6:30 p.m.
(d) Upstream and downstream connected parties must confirm with Transporter no later than 8:30 p.m.
(e) Transporter will provide scheduled quantities to affected Shippers and point operators at their Designated Site, and will provide notice to Bumped parties, by 9:00 p.m. on the Day prior to flow.
(f) Scheduled quantities resulting from an Evening Nomination that do not cause another Shipper on the System to receive notice that it is being Bumped will be effective at 9:00 a.m. on the next gas Day; and when an Evening Nomination that causes another Shipper on the System to receive notice that it is being Bumped, the scheduled quantities will be effective at 9:00 a.m. on the next gas Day.
6.8 Intra-Day 1 Nomination Cycle:
(a) Nominations must leave the control of the nominating party by 10:00 a.m.
(b) Nominations must be received by Transporter by 10:15 a.m. (including from Title Transfer Tracking service providers).
Transporter will send a Quick Response by 10:30 a.m.
(c) Upstream and downstream connected parties must confirm with Transporter no later than 12:30 p.m.
(d) Transporter will provide scheduled quantities to Shippers and point operators at their designated Site, and will provide notice to Bumped parties, by -1:00 p.m.
(e) Scheduled quantities resulting from Intra-day 1 nominations will be effective at -2:00 p.m. on gas Day.
6.9 Intra-Day 2 Nomination Cycle:
(a) Nominations must leave the control of the nominating party by 2:30 p.m.
(b) Nominations must be received by Transporter by 2:45 p.m. (including from Title Transfer racking service providers).
(c) Transporter will send a Quick Response by 3:00 p.m.
(d) Upstream and downstream connected parties must confirm with Transporter no later than 5:00 p.m.
(e) Transporter will provide scheduled quantities to affected Shippers and point operators at their Designated Site and will provide notice to Bumped parties by 5:30 p.m.
(f) Scheduled quantities resulting from Intra-Day 2 Nominations will be effective at 6:00 p.m. on gas Day. .
6.10 Intra-Day 3 Nomination Cycle:
(a) Nominations must leave the control of the nominating party by 7:00 p.m.
(b) Nominations must be received by Transporter by 7:15 p.m. (including from Title Transfer Tracking service providers).
(c) Transporter will send a Quick Response by 7:30 p.m.
(d) Upstream and downstream connected parties must confirm with Transporter no later than 9:30 p.m.
Transporter will provide scheduled quantities to affected Shippers and point operators at their Designated Site by 10:00 p.m.
(e) Scheduled quantities resulting from Intra-Day 2 Nominations will be effective at 10:00 p.m. on gas Day. Bumping is not allowed during the Intra-day 2 Nomination cycle.
6.11 Confirmation of Nominated Quantities.
(a) All nominations will be confirmed by the upstream or downstream connected party through the Internet Website or EDI. At least one Confirming Party should be on each side of a physical location.
(b) With respect to the timely nomination or confirmation process at a Receipt Point or Delivery Point, in the absence of agreement to the contrary, the lesser of the confirmation quantities will be the confirmed quantity. If a Shipper does not respond to a request for confirmation or if the confirmation response is unsolicited, the lesser of the confirmation quantity or the previously scheduled quantity will be the new confirmed quantity.
(c) With respect to the processing of requests for increases during the intra-day nomination or confirmation process, in the absence of agreement to the contrary, the lesser of the confirmation quantities will be the new confirmed quantity. If a Shipper does not respond to a request for confirmation or if the confirmation response is unsolicited, the previously scheduled quantity will be the new confirmed quantity.
(d) With respect to the processing of requests for decreases during the intra-day nomination or confirmation process, in the absence of agreement to the contrary, the lesser of the confirmation quantities will be the new confirmed quantity, but in any event no less than the quantity remaining after Elapsed-Prorated-Scheduled Quantity has been apportioned. If a Shipper does not respond to a request for confirmation or if the confirmation response is unsolicited, the greater of the confirmation quantity or the Elapsed-Prorated-Scheduled Quantity will be the new confirmed quantity.
(e) With respect to Sections 6.6, 6.7, 6.8, and 6.9 of these General Terms and Conditions, if no response to a request for confirmation is made by Transporter or an unsolicited confirmation response, Transporter will provide the service requester with the following information to explain why the nomination failed, as applicable:
(i) The service requester's TSP did not conduct the confirmation;
(ii) The service requester is told by TSP that the upstream Confirming Party did not conduct the confirmation;
(iii) The service requester is told by TSP that the upstream service requester did not have the gas or submit the nomination;
The service requester is told by TSP that the downstream Confirming Party did not conduct the confirmation; and
(iv) The service requester is told by TSP that the downstream service requester did not have the market or submit the nomination.
(f) This information will be imparted to the service requester on the scheduled quantity document.
(g) The explicit confirmation process requires that the Confirming Party respond to a request for confirmation or initiate an unsolicited confirmation response. Absent mutual agreement to the contrary, explicit confirmation is the default methodology.
(h) For request to confirm and confirmation response processes, all parties will seek to confirm by means of communicating at the applicable detail and summary level all transactions with respect to a location.
(i) In the confirmation process, where a party requesting confirmation (a Confirmation Requester) is not itself a TSP, the location code to be used when sending a Request for Confirmation should be the location code associated with the location where gas will be scheduled by the TSP; and, where a Confirmation Requester is also a TSP, then, as between the Confirmation Requester and the Confirming Parties, and absent their mutual agreement to the contrary, the location code to be used when sending a Request for Confirmation should be the location code used by the TSP sending the Request for Confirmation.
6.12 Bumping and Intra-Day Limitations.
(a) For services that provide for Intra-Day Nominations and scheduling, the number of Intra-Day Nominations which a service requester may submit at any one standard nomination cycle or in total across all standard nomination cycles is not limited.
(b) Transporter will permit Intra-Day Nominations (1) to increase or decrease total flow, (2) to change Receipt Points, (3) to change Delivery Points; and (4) to schedule new Receipt or Delivery Points.
(c) Intra-Day Nominations are permitted at all Receipt Points and Delivery Points.
6.13 Bump Protection for Firm Services. Transporter will not schedule an Intra-Day Nomination related to any Firm Transportation Service if such change will Bump scheduled and flowing Firm Transportation Service. Transporter will not schedule an Intra-Day Nomination related to any Firm Transportation Service if such change will Bump scheduled and flowing of a lower priority service unless the nomination change is an intra-day change for a Primary or Secondary Receipt Point under the Shipper's Gas Transportation Agreement.
(a) Bumping that affects transactions on multiple TSPs will occur at grid-wide synchronization times only.
(b) If Transporter exceeds the standard nomination time line, Transporter is not required to hold capacity for grid-wide nominations until a standard nomination cycle.
All nominations, including Intra-Day Nominations, must be based on a daily quantity, thus, an intra-day nominator need not submit an hourly nomination. Intra-Day Nomination should include an effective date and time. The interconnected parties should agree on the hourly flows of the Intra-Day Nomination if not otherwise addressed in the Transporter's contract or tariff.
6.14 Bumping Scheduled Quantities.
(a) When a previously confirmed and scheduled quantity is altered, notification of such alteration will be provided through the affected party's choice of Electronic Notice Delivery mechanism or phone; unless Transporter and Shippers have agreed to the exclusive use of EDI, Shippers must provide Transporter with at least one internet E-mail address to be used for Electronic Notice Delivery of intra-day Bumps. Provided that Transporter will not permit Bumping resulting from an Intra-Day Nomination submitted at the Intra-Day 2 Nomination Cycle. Transporter will support the concurrent sending of electronic notification of intra-day Bumps to two internet E- mail addresses for each Shipper. Such E-mail will include a subject line that includes the following information in the following manner:
(i) "Critical,"
(ii) Notice Type label,
(iii) The Notice Effective Date in YYYYMMDD format,
(iv) "Transporter," and
(v) Transporter's DUNS Number.
(b) In addition, the notice will indicate the affected service requester contract, Receipt or Delivery Points, and Receipt or Delivery Point maximum quantities from the scheduled quantity. Notification of alteration will be provided to all parties below that are affected.
(i) Confirmation Requester in a confirmation response (or unsolicited confirmation response as applicable) document by the Confirming Party;
(ii) Confirming Party in a request for confirmation document by the Confirmation Requester; and
(iii) Service requesters in a scheduled quantity document by the applicable Confirming Party or Confirmation Requester on whose system the service requester's nominations were made.
(c) Applicable notifications of such alterations will be provided to the affected parties reasonably proximate in time to the time during which the event causing the alteration was acted upon by the Confirmation Requester or Confirming Party, respectively. With respect to the implementation of this process via NAESB Standards 1.4.x, Confirmation Requester and Confirming Party will send the applicable documents to the applicable party no later than the next time they are slated to communicate confirmations or scheduled quantities (as applicable).
6.15 Rollover Prohibition. Intra-Day Nominations do not rollover (i.e. Intra-Day Nominations span one (1) Day only). Intra-Day Nominations do not replace the remainder of a standing nomination. There is no need to re-nominate if Intra-Day Nomination modifies existing nomination.
6.16 Hourly Flow Limitations. Transporter will attempt to agree with the interconnected parties on the hourly flows for Intra-Day Nominations.
6.17 Bumped Interruptible Shippers - Daily Penalties. Interruptible Shippers that are Bumped as a result of the Intra-Day Nomination process will be subject to daily penalties only during Critical Days.
6.18 Firm Shipper Intra-Day Nominations. Intra-Day Nominations by a firm Shipper will have scheduling priority over the nominated and scheduled quantities of interruptible Shippers. Interruptible Shippers whose volumes are Bumped as a result of Intra-Day Nominations by firm Shippers will be provided advance notice of such Bump via telephone or email. This notice will indicate whether a critical penalty is in effect on the day the interruptible Shipper's volumes are being reduced.
6.19 Fuel, Lost, and Unaccounted-for Gas. The formula for calculating FL&A for nominations is:
(a) (1 - (Fuel, Lost and Unaccounted-For Gas Percentage/100)) multiplied by receipt quantity = delivery quantity.
(b) The result of the calculation will be rounded to the nearest Dth for each nomination.
6.20 Nomination Changes. All nominations should be considered original nominations and should be replaced to be changed. When a nomination for a date range is received, each Day within that range is considered an original nomination. When a subsequent nomination is received for one or more Days within that range, the previous nomination is superseded by the subsequent nomination only to the extent of the Days specified. The Days of the previous nomination outside the range of the subsequent nomination are unaffected. Nominations have a prospective effect only.
6.21 Authorized Overrun Nominations. Nominations for quantities in excess of the Firm MDQ for service under Rate Schedule FTS or FTS-N must be nominated as a separate transaction. Authorized Overrun Nominations will be treated as transportation under Rate Schedule ITS or ITS-N, as applicable.
6.22 Rankings. Shippers may provide rankings for gas nominated for receipt and delivery. Nominations without a ranking will be scheduled on a pro rata basis. Priority 1 means the highest priority. Priorities 2, 3, etc. are in descending order of priority. Quantities assigned the same rank will be scheduled and curtailed on a pro rata basis. Transporter will use the Shipper-provided rankings when making reductions during the scheduling process when this does not conflict with tariff-based rules.
6.23 Package Identification Code. Transporter will support the use of Package ID for nominating, scheduling, and invoicing (sales and purchases), and mutually agree with applicable parties regarding transportation, allocation, and imbalance reporting. The Shipper may assign a Package ID to each nomination.
6.24 Required Nomination Changes. Transporter may require revised nominations or prospective nomination changes by Shipper if the daily flows under a particular Service Agreement differ from confirmed nominations, or if an imbalance has occurred due to some operational reason. When a Shipper receives notice requiring a revised nomination or prospective nomination change, Shipper shall submit a nomination in accordance with this Section 6 of these General Terms and Conditions and with the revisions specified by Transporter.
6.25 Delegation of Nomination Authority to Agent. A Shipper may delegate to any third party the responsibility for submitting nominations and receiving confirmations or performing other administrative duties under any Service Agreement, subject to the following conditions:
(a) Any designation of a third party as agent, or any change in such designation, must be provided in writing to Transporter at least two (2) Business Days prior to the requested effective date of the designation.
(b) The written designation shall specify any limits on the authority of the Agent, including any time limit for the designation.
(c) Transporter will rely on communications from a Shipper's Agent for all nomination purposes except to the extent the designation is explicitly limited. Limitations must be clearly specified. Shipper will hold Transporter harmless and shall Indemnify Transporter for any Losses incurred by Transporter in the event Transporter's good faith interpretation of a limitation proves inconsistent with the intent of the limitation. Transporter reserves the right to reject delegations for reasons of unclear or impracticable limitations placed thereon. Communications by Transporter to such Agent shall be deemed notice to Shipper except to the extent the Agent's authority is explicitly limited as follows:
(i) With respect to the receipt of notice, the provisions of Section 17 of these General Terms and Conditions.
(ii) With respect to an Agent for one or more Shippers, any third party may administer multiple Service Agreements; however, the Agent shall administer and account separately for each Service Agreement.
(iii) With respect to an agent's authority, each Agent must execute the Agency Agreement in the form posted on Transporter's Internet Website prior to being authorized to act for a Shipper. 6.26 Electronic Notice Delivery. For the purposes of Sections 7.4 through 7.8 of these General Terms and Conditions, all notices will be sent by Electronic Notice Delivery. Transporter will support the concurrent sending of electronic notification of Critical Notices to two internet E-mail addresses for each Shipper. Unless Transporter and Shippers have agreed to the exclusive use of EDI, Shippers must provide Transporter with at least one internet e-mail address to be used for Electronic Notice Delivery of Critical Notices.
6.27 Quick Response for Nominations Outside Timely/Intra-Day Nomination Schedule.
(a) With the exception of otherwise stated NAESB nominations deadlines, when Transporter receives a Nomination document from a service requester by the conclusion of a given quarter hour period, Transporter will send to the service requester's designated site a corresponding Quick Response document by the conclusion of the subsequent quarter hour period.
(b) Transporter's nightly processing and routine maintenance occurring outside of normal business hours are apt to interrupt the normal schedule for nominations or quick response turnaround stated in NAESB Standards. Such delays should be kept to a minimum. The normal schedule should be resumed at the earliest opportunity and no later than the start of normal working hours the following day, seven (7) days per week.
6.28 Confirmation Quick Response Outside Timely/Intra-day Nomination Schedule.
(a) When a Confirmation Requester receives a Confirmation Response document from a Confirming Party by the conclusion of a given quarter hour period, the Confirmation Requester will send to the Confirming Party's Designated Site a corresponding Confirmation Response Quick Response document by the conclusion of the subsequent quarter hour period. The quarter hour periods will be defined to begin on the hour and at 15, 30, and 45 minutes past the hour. A given quarter hour will contain all transactions whose receipt time is less than the beginning of the subsequent quarter hour.
(b) Confirmation Requester's and Confirming Party's nightly processing and routine maintenance occurring outside of normal business hours are apt to interrupt the normal schedule for confirmations or quick response turnaround stated in NAESB Standards. Such delays should be kept to a minimum. The normal schedule should be resumed at the earliest opportunity and no later than the start of normal working hours the following Day, seven days per week.
6.29 Segmentation of Firm Capacity.
(a) Shipper or a Replacement Shipper may divide the transportation service of its FTS or FTS-N Agreement into segments of firm service either for its own use, provided that:
(i) The total Firm MDQs of the combined services applicable to a segment do not exceed the Firm MDQ in Shipper's FTS or FTS-N Agreements; and
(ii) It is operationally feasible for Transporter to provide firm service on the service segments.
(b) A Shipper (including a Replacement Shipper) under an FTS or FTS-N Agreement may nominate segments between a Primary Receipt and Delivery Point, provided that any resulting overlap does not exceed Shipper's Firm MDQ at any Receipt Point or Delivery Point on any segment (or portion) of the System. Any portion of that segmented transaction that flows in the opposite direction of the Shipper's primary path will be considered out of the path for scheduling and segmentation purposes. Where a service segment is released to a Replacement Shipper, the Releasing, and Replacement Shippers shall be treated as separate Shippers with separate Service Agreements and Firm MDQs. Thus, the Releasing Shipper may seek changes in the Primary Receipt and Primary Delivery Points on the unreleased segments up to the Firm MDQ for that unreleased segment, and the Replacement Shipper with the consent of the Releasing Shipper may simultaneously seek changes to the Primary Receipt and Primary Delivery Points on the released segment up to the Firm MDQ for that released segment. The Releasing Shipper and the Replacement Shipper may further segment and release its service segments subject to the limitations specified herein and the capacity release provisions in Section 12 of these General Terms and Conditions. The Replacement Shipper may also use Secondary Receipt and Delivery Points on the System.
(c) Notwithstanding the foregoing, neither Shipper nor any Replacement Shipper shall be entitled to segment the receipts and deliveries of gas at the Receipt Points except to the extent that their combined use of the Receipt Points does not exceed the Shipper's Firm MDQ. Accordingly, under an FTS or FTS-N Agreement, the sum of the receipts of gas by Transporter at all of the Receipt Points shall equal the sum of the deliveries of gas at all of the Delivery Points, less FL&A.
